iversal Pictures\n|-\n| ''[[The Two Faces of January (film)|The Two Faces of January]]'' || April 16, 2014 || Distributed by Universal Pictures\n|-\n| ''[[Elle l'adore]]'' || June 18, 2014 ||\n|-\n| ''[[The House of Magic]]'' || July 25, 2014 ||\n|-\n| ''[[Before I Go to Sleep (film)|Before I Go to Sleep]]'' || September 4, 2014 || Distributed by [[20th Century Fox]]\n|-\n| ''[[The Imitation Game]]'' || November 21, 2014 || Distributed by [[The Weinstein Company]]<br>Nominee of the Academy Award for Best Picture\n|-\n| ''[[Paddington (film)|Paddington]]'' || December 12, 2014 || Distributed by StudioCanal; licensed to [[The Weinstein Company]] in North America\n|-\n| ''[[Shaun the Sheep Movie]]'' || February 6, 2015 || Distributed by [[Lionsgate|Lions Gate Entertainment]]<br />Production company [[Aardman Animations]]<br /> Nominee of [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature|the Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]] \n|-\n| ''[[The Gunman (2015 film)|The Gunman]]'' || March 20, 2015 || Distributed by [[Open Road Films]]\n|-\n| ''[[Carol (film)|Carol]]'' || May 17, 2015 [[2015 Cannes Film Festival|(Cannes)]] || Distributed by StudioCanal and [[The Weinstein Company]]<br />Production companies [[Number 9 Films]] \u00b7 [[Killer Films]] \u00b7 [[Film4 Productions]]\n|-\n| ''[[Man Up (film)|Man Up]]'' || May 29, 2015 ||\n|-\n| ''[[We Are Your Friends (film)|We Are Your Friends]]'' || August 28, 2015 || Distributed by Warner Bros.\n|-\n| ''[[Legend (2015 film)|Legend]]'' || September 9, 2015 || Distributed by Universal Pictures\n|-\n| ''[[Macbeth (2015 film)|Macbeth]]'' || October 2, 2015 || Distributed by The Weinstein Company\n|-\n| ''[[The Program (2015 film)|The Program]]'' || October 16, 2015 || Distributed by [[Momentum Pictures]]\n|-\n| ''[[Youth (2015 film)|Youth]]'' || January 29, 2016 || Distributed by [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]]\n|-\n| ''[[A Bigger Splash (2015 film)|A Bigger Splash]]'' || February 12, 2016 || Distributed by Fox Searchlight Pictures\n|-\n| ''[[Bastille Day (2016 film)|Bastille Day]]'' || April 22, 2016 || Distributed by Focus Features\n|-\n| ''[[Knight of Cups (film)|Knight of Cups]]'' || May 6, 2016 || Distributed by [[Broad Green Pictures]]\n|-\n| ''[[Our Kind of Traitor (film)|Our Kind of Traitor]]'' || July 1, 2016 || Distributed by [[Roadside Attractions]]\n|-\n| ''[[Swallows and Amazons (2016 film)|Swallows and Amazons]]'' || August 19, 2016 ||\n|-\n| ''[[Hell or High Water (2016 film)|Hell or High Water]]'' || August 26, 2016 || Distributed by [[Lionsgate]]\n|-\n| ''[[Dance Academy: The Movie]]'' || April 6, 2017 || Distributed by StudioCanal\n|-\n| ''[[Mindhorn]]'' || May 5, 2017 || Distributed by StudioCanal\n|-\n|''[[Jalouse]]'' || November 8, 2017 || Distributed by StudioCanal\n|-\n|''[[Paddington 2]]'' || November 12, 2017 || Distributed by StudioCanal; licensed to [[Warner Bros.]] in North America and Spain\n|-\n| ''[[Early Man (film)|Early Man]]'' || January 26, 2018 ||  Distributed by [[Lionsgate|Lions Gate Entertainment]]<br />Production company [[Aardman Animations]]  \n|-\n| ''[[The Mercy]]'' || February 9, 2018 ||\n|-\n| ''[[Entebbe (film)|7 Days in Entebbe]]'' || March 16, 2018 || Distributed by Focus Features\n|-\n| ''[[The Guernsey Literary and Potato Peel Pie Society (film)|The Guernsey Literary and Potato Peel Pie Society]]'' || April 20, 2018 || Production company Blueprint Pictures\n|-\n| ''[[Yardie (film)|Yardie]]'' || August 24, 2018 || Distributed by [[StudioCanal UK]]\n|-\n| ''[[Johnny English Strikes Again]]'' || October 12, 2018 || Distributed by Universal Pictures\n|-\n| ''[[Cold Pursuit]]'' || February 8, 2019 || Distributed by [[Summit Entertainment]]\n|-\n|''[[A Shaun the Sheep Movie: Farmageddon]]''|| 18 October 2019 ||  Distributed by [[Lionsgate|Lions Gate Entertainment]]<br />Production company [[Aardman Animations]] \n|}\n\n===2020s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Title\n! Release date\n! Notes\n|-\n| ''[[Chicken Run 2]]'' || TBA ||  Distributed by [[Lionsgate|Lions Gate Entertainment]]<br />Production company [[Path\u00e9]] and [[Aardman Animations]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.studiocanal.com/}}\n*[http://www.studiocanal.com/en/studiocanal-group/historical Official history]\n\n{{Vivendi}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Studiocanal}}\n[[Category:Canal+ Group]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Film production companies of France]]\n[[Category:Film production companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Film distributors of France]]\n[[Category:Film distributors of the United States]]\n[[Category:StudioCanal films]]\n[[Category:Vivendi subsidiaries]]\n", "name_user": "Skywatcher68", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2010s:StudioCanal helped produce these films and also acted as an EU distrubutor.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/StudioCanal"}
{"title_page": "Simon Stevens (healthcare manager)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2014}} \n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = Sir \n| name = Simon Stevens\n| image = Simon Stevens NHS 225x300.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| office = Chief Executive of [[NHS England]]\n| term_start = 1 April 2014\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[David Nicholson (civil servant)|Sir David Nicholson]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Lambeth London Borough Council|Lambeth Borough Councillor]] for Angell Ward\n| term_start1 = 7 May 1998\n| term_end1 = 2 May 2002\n| predecessor1 = \n| successor1 = \n| birth_date = <!--{{birth date and age|| | |df=y}}-->\n| birth_place = [[Shard End]], [[Birmingham]], England\n| birth_name =\n| nationality = \n| relations = \n| spouse = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Balliol College, Oxford]]<br>[[University of Strathclyde]]\n| occupation = \n| religion = \n| website = \n}}\n'''Sir Simon Laurence Stevens''' (born 4 August 1966) is a British [[Health management|health manager]] and public policy analyst. His appointment<ref>{{Cite press release |url= http://www.england.nhs.uk/2013/10/24/simon-stevens-appoint/|title=Simon Stevens Appointed as new Chief Executive of NHS England |publisher=NHS England |date=24 October 2013 |access-date=19 March 2016}}</ref> as the eighth [[Chief Executives of the NHS|Chief Executive]] of the [[NHS England|National Health Service in England]] with effect from 1 April 2014 was announced in October 2013, succeeding [[David Nicholson (civil servant)|David Nicholson]]. He was said by the ''[[Health Service Journal]]'' in December 2013 to be the second most powerful person in the English NHS, even before he took up his appointment.<ref>{{cite news|title=HSJ100 2013 The annual list of the most influential people in health|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/leadership/hsj-100/|accessdate=14 December 2013|newspaper=Health Service Journal|date=11 December 2013}}</ref> He has stayed top of their list of the most influential people in health ever since.<ref>{{cite news |title=HSJ100 full list: Stevens tops table for fifth year |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/hsj100/hsj100-full-list-stevens-tops-table-for-fifth-year/7023990.article |accessdate=22 January 2019 |work=Health Service Journal |date=13 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSimon Stevens was born in [[Birmingham]], England,<ref name=\"whoswho2017bio\">{{cite web|title=STEVENS, Simon Laurence|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U272409|website=Who's Who 2017|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> the son of a Baptist minister and a university administrator.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boseley|first=Sarah|date=21 June 2014|title=Simon Stevens: visionary Chief Executive of NHS England|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(14)61019-9/abstract|journal=The Lancet |volume=383 |issue=9935 |page=2117 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(14)61019-9|issn=0140-6736|pmid=24953466}}</ref> He was educated at a state comprehensive, [[St. Bartholomew's School]], and won a scholarship to [[Balliol College, Oxford]] University, where he was elected president of the [[Oxford Union]]. His friends at Balliol reportedly ranged from [[Extinction Rebellion]]'s [[Rupert Read]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08byj3g|title=BBC Radio 4 - Profile, Simon Stevens|website=BBC |access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref> to [[Boris Johnson]] who credited Stevens with Johnson's own election as Oxford Union president.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/25/boris-johnson-filmed-telling-tory-members-nhs-needs-reform |title=Boris Johnson filmed telling Tory members NHS 'needs reform' |last=Mason |first=Rowena |date=25 June 2019 |work=The Guardian |location= London |access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/how-a-young-boris-johnson-bonded-with-nhs-chief-simon-stevens-jc28c080r|title=How a young Boris Johnson bonded with NHS chief Simon Stevens |last=Courea|first=Eleni|date=6 August 2019|work=The Times|access-date=6 October 2019 |location= London}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/08/07/future-pm-boris-johnson-nhs-boss-simon-stevens-formed-unlikely/|title=How the future PM, Boris Johnson, and NHS boss, Simon Stevens, formed an unlikely bond at Oxford |last=Bird |first=Steve |date=7 August 2019 |work=The Telegraph |location= London |access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"kuper\">{{cite news |last1=Kuper |first1=Simon |title=How Oxford university shaped Brexit \u2014 and Britain's next prime minister |url=https://www.ft.com/content/85fc694c-9222-11e9-b7ea-60e35ef678d2 |accessdate=21 June 2019 |work=Financial Times |location= London |date=21 June 2019}}</ref> Stevens later received an MBA from the [[University of Strathclyde]], Glasgow and was a [[Harkness Fellowship|Harkness Fellow]] at [[Columbia University]], New York. His wife, Maggie, is a public health specialist from New York City. Their son was born on Christmas Day 2003 at [[St Thomas' Hospital]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/oct/24/simon-stevens-interview|title=The NHS is a social movement|last=|first=|date=24 October 2014|work=|accessdate=25 October 2014|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> and their daughter in 2008.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/10864008/Simon-Stevens-The-NHS-is-at-a-defining-moment.html |title=Simon Stevens: 'The NHS is at a defining moment' |last=Donnelly |first=Laura |date=29 May 2014 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==NHS==\nAfter university Stevens first worked in [[Guyana]],<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Simon Stevens: visionary Chief Executive of NHS England|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(14)61019-9/fulltext|journal=The Lancet|volume=383|page=2117|via=|pmid=24953466|year=2014|last1=Boseley|first1=S.|issue=9935|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(14)61019-9}}</ref> and then from 1988 to 1997 as a healthcare manager in the UK and internationally. He started his NHS career on the [http://www.nhsgraduates.co.uk NHS Graduate Management Training Scheme] at Shotley Bridge General Hospital, the largest employer in [[Consett]], County Durham, after the closure of the [[Consett Steel Works|steel works]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/nhs-chief-simon-stevens-goes-6905643 |title=NHS chief Simon Stevens goes back to North East roots |last=Rae |first=Helen |date=2 April 2014 |newspaper=Evening Chronicle |location= Newcastle |access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release |url= https://www.england.nhs.uk/2014/04/simon-stevens-speech/ |date=1 April 2014 |publisher=NHS England |title=Full text of Simon Stevens' speech |website=www.england.nhs.uk |access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref>  After a spell in [[Republic of the Congo|Congo]] and [[Malawi]], he became general manager for [http://www.mark-davis-photography.com/explore/st-georges-hospital-morpeth/ a large NHS psychiatric hospital outside Newcastle-upon-Tyne], and ran community mental health services for North Tyneside and Northumberland. He was then appointed group manager of [[Guy's and St Thomas' NHS Foundation Trust|Guy's and St Thomas' hospitals]] in London<ref>{{cite press release |url= https://www.guysandstthomas.nhs.uk/news-and-events/2015-news/november/20151104-simon-stevens-speaks-at-veterans-agm.aspx |title=Simon Stevens at Guys and St Thomas' |date=4 November 2015 |publisher=Guys and St Thomas' NHS Foundation Trust }}</ref> before moving to [[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene|New York City Health Department]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-272409|title=Stevens, Simon Laurence, (born 4 Aug. 1966), Chief Executive, NHS England, since 2014 {{!}} WHO'S WHO & WHO WAS WHO|website=www.ukwhoswho.com|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U272409|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Government ==\nIn 1997 he was appointed policy adviser to two successive [[Secretaries of State for Health]] ([[Frank Dobson]] and [[Alan Milburn]]) at the UK [[Department of Health and Social Care|Department of Health]]. From 2001 to 2004 he was the Government's health policy adviser in the [[Number 10 Policy Unit]] to [[Tony Blair]] at [[10 Downing Street]]. Stevens was a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] councillor for [[Brixton]], in the [[London Borough of Lambeth]] 1998\u20132002. He was closely associated with the development of the [[NHS Plan 2000]].\n\n== UnitedHealth ==\nFrom 2004 to 2014 Stevens was a senior executive at [https://www.unitedhealthgroup.com UnitedHealth Group]. Initially appointed president of UnitedHealth Europe, he became CEO of UnitedHealthcare's $30 billion Medicare business, and then corporate Executive Vice President and president of its global health businesses spanning the Americas, Europe, Asia, and Africa. He also was a director of Brazil's largest hospital group [http://www.amil.com.br AMIL].\n\nHe was instrumental in establishing a non-profit institute to publish information about inefficiency in the US health system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.healthcostinstitute.org|title=Health Care Cost Institute}}</ref> These data proved that contrary to prior research mainly using Medicare data, cost differences in the working age population were a result not mainly because of differences in service utilisation but also because of market pricing power by hospitals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/12/15/upshot/the-best-places-for-better-cheaper-health-care-arent-what-experts-thought.html,%20https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/12/15/upshot/the-best-places-for-better-cheaper-health-care-arent-what-experts-thought.html|title=The Experts Were Wrong About the Best Places for Better and Cheaper Health Care |last=Quealy |first=Kevin|date=15 December 2015 |work=The New York Times|access-date=6 October 2019|last2=Sanger-Katz|first2=Margot }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.modernhealthcare.com/article/20190204/NEWS/190209984/hospital-price-growth-driving-healthcare-spending |title=Hospital price growth driving healthcare spending |date=4 February 2019|website=Modern Healthcare |access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe also served on the boards of various non-profits, including the [[Minnesota Historical Society]]; the [[Minnesota Opera]]; and the [[Medicare Rights Center]] (New York), as well as the [[King's Fund]] and the [[Nuffield Trust]].\n\n==Chief executive of NHS England==\n\nAs the [[Chief Executives of the NHS|NHS England CEO]], he is directly accountable to Parliament for management of \u00a3120 billion of annual NHS funding. He frequently gives evidence to the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]], the House of Commons Health and Social Care Committee, and other Parliamentary committees. He has used the statutory independence of NHS England to speak openly about NHS funding and reform.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/sites/default/files/publications/World%27s%20Biggest%20Quango%20NHS%20England%20web.pdf|title=The first five years of NHS England|last=Timmins|first=Nicholas}}</ref> In January 2019 he welcomed new figures from the [[Office for National Statistics]] showing that NHS productivity in England has been rising at 3%, treble the performance of the overall UK economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2019/01/skill-and-dedication-of-nhs-staff-praised-as-health-service-productivity-outstrips-the-rest-of-the-economy/|title=NHS England \u00bb Skill and dedication of NHS staff praised as health service productivity outstrips the rest of the economy|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pharmafield.co.uk/pharma_news/nhs-staff-praised-as-productivity-grows/|title=NHS staff praised as productivity grows|last=Schofield|first=Amy|date=23 April 2019 |website=Pharmafield |access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn his return to the NHS, ''The Guardian'' reported one health expert as saying \"He's coming back to a pay cut [and] the mother of all messes\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/jan/18/simon-stevens-trying-save-nhs-from-mother-of-messes|title=Simon Stevens \u2013 trying to steer the NHS through tumultuous times|last=|first=|date=|work=The Guardian|access-date=}}</ref> Stevens' own assessment was that \"For the NHS the stakes have never been higher. The global recession has meant the NHS facing its most sustained budget crunch in its history. Service pressures are intensifying, and longstanding problems are not going to disappear overnight.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2014/04/simon-stevens-speech/|title=NHS England \u00bb Full text of Simon Stevens' speech|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> Stevens said his aim was to '''\"'''Think like a patient, act like a taxpayer.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/jan/18/simon-stevens-trying-save-nhs-from-mother-of-messes |title=Simon Stevens: trying to steer the NHS through tumultuous times |last=Johnson |first=Paul |date=18 January 2016 |work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019 |location= London }}</ref> As of 2015, Stevens was paid a salary of between \u00a3190,000 and \u00a3194,999 by NHS England<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/492289/150K_senior_salaries.csv/preview|title=Senior officials 'high earners' salaries as at 30 September 2015 \u2013 GOV.UK|date=17 December 2015|website=www.gov.uk|access-date=13 March 2016}}</ref> and each year he has opted for a voluntary \u00a320,000 pay cut.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/nhs/10400660/Blair-advisor-Simon-Stevens-appointed-new-NHS-chief-executive.html|title=Blair advisor Simon Stevens appointed new NHS chief executive|last=Donnelly|first=Laura|date=23 October 2013|access-date=26 January 2019|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> According to [[Fraser Nelson]], hiring Stevens back to run NHS England was one of the cleverest moves that [[David Cameron]] made because he \"knows more about NHS problems and market solutions than any man alive\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/fraser-nelson/2014/10/the-nhs-wales-disaster-vindicates-tony-blair-not-david-cameron/|title=The NHS Wales disaster vindicates Tony Blair, not David Cameron|date=24 October 2014|accessdate=25 October 2014|publisher=The Spectator}}</ref> During the 2019 General Election campaign while the Labour Party said they would generally not comment on the appointments of public officials, they stated they have a \"good relationship with Simon Stevens and respect him.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.hsj.co.uk/leadership/labour-voices-respect-for-nhs-chief-simon-stevens/7026365.article |title=Labour voices 'respect' for NHS chief Simon Stevens |date=13 November 2019 |last=Dunhill |first=Lawrence|website=Health Service Journal |access-date=26 December 2019}}</ref> In March 2019 it was announced Stevens would also lead the hospital regulator, NHS Improvement, effectively merging it into NHS England.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.onmedica.com/newsArticle.aspx?id=2caa55b9-7ab2-47f8-b18a-4fff654b6a94|title=OnMedica - News - NHS Improvement set to merge with NHS England|website=www.onmedica.com|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nStevens was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the [[2020 New Year Honours]] for services to the NHS.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62866|supp=y|page=N2|date=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== NHS Five Year Forward View ===\nHe was responsible for the [[Five Year Forward View]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=71HWJXufqlM|title=NHS Five Year Forward View video}}</ref> produced by NHS England in October 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kingsfund.org.uk/blog/2014/10/nhs-five-year-forward-view-man-matters-more-plan|title=The NHS five year forward view: the man matters more than the plan|date=27 October 2014|website=The King's Fund|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> This marked the beginning of a major shift in how NHS care is delivered, in contrast to NHS policy since 1991. Instead care is increasingly being redesigned to achieve what Stevens labelled the \"triple integration\" of primary and specialist care, physical and mental health services, and NHS and social care.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2014/06/simon-stevens-speech-confed/|title=NHS England \u00bb Speech by Simon Stevens, CEO NHS England, to the NHS Confederation Annual Conference 2014|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2015/05/fit-for-future/|title=NHS England \u00bb Simon Stevens call for bold action to make NHS fit for the future|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> He has however recently challenged the longstanding assumption that this will mean there is a need for fewer hospital beds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/jun/19/hospital-bed-cutbacks-have-gone-too-far-nhs-england-boss-simon-stevens-says|title=Hospital bed cutbacks have gone too far, NHS England boss says|last=Campbell |first=Denis|date=19 June 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019 |location= London }}</ref>\n\nStevens has also prioritised the modernisation of NHS primary care,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/gpfv.pdf|title=The NHS GP Forward View}}</ref> mental health and cancer care<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/cancer/|title=NHS England \u00bb Cancer|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> having commissioned an independent national taskforce led by Sir Harpal Kumar the chief executive of Cancer Research UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cancerresearchuk.org/about-us/cancer-strategy-in-england|title=Cancer Strategy in England|date=10 March 2017|website=Cancer Research UK|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> Breast cancer deaths have subsequently fallen faster than in other large European countries and outcomes are estimated to have caught up with or surpassed the European average.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/mar/19/uk-breast-cancer-death-rates-falling-fastest-in-big-six-of-europe|title=UK breast cancer death rates falling fastest in 'big six' of Europe|last=Campbell|first=Denis|date=19 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> In 2015 he commissioned the independent [https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Mental-Health-Taskforce-FYFV-final.pdf Five Year Forward View for mental health] chaired by Paul Farmer the head of MIND.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mind.org.uk/news-campaigns/news/paul-farmer-to-chair-mental-health-taskforce/#.XExlMi2cZyo |title=Paul Farmer to chair mental health taskforce |work=Mind.org.uk |date=25 March 2015}}</ref> He subsequently directed that each year local mental health spending must rise faster than overall NHS funding growth.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/health-44651742|title=Mental health services need 'major ramp up' |work=BBC News |date=29 June 2018|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> Given increasing concerns about young people\u2019s mental health and eating disorders, he voiced concern on the BBC's Andrew Marr show about cosmetic surgery adverts during ITV's ''[[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 4)|Love Island]]'' series.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} Shortly after, ITV's chief executive agreed to reconsider the ads,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2018/jul/25/itv-to-review-use-of-plastic-surgery-and-diet-ads-during-love-island|title=ITV to review use of plastic surgery and diet ads during Love Island|last=Waterson|first=Jim|date=25 July 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019|last2=Sweney|first2=Mark |location= London}}</ref> and the Advertising Standards Authority went on to ban them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/oct/17/breast-enlargement-ads-shown-during-love-island-banned-by-asa|title=Breast enlargement ads shown during Love Island banned by ASA|last=Rawlinson|first=Kevin|date=16 October 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> He\u00a0has suggested that social media companies might be asked to contribute to funding improved mental health support for young people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/10/10/facebook-instagram-should-pay-mental-health-levy-nhs-damage/|title=Facebook should pay a 'mental health' levy for the damage it causes, says NHS boss |last=Donnelly |first=Laura|date=10 October 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=27 January 2019 |location= London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sbcnews.co.uk/retail/2018/09/07/gambleaware-backs-nhs-criticism-of-betting-footballs-failure-to-tackle-problem-gambling/|title=GambleAware backs NHS criticism of betting & football's failure to tackle problem gambling|date=7 September 2018|website=SBC News|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> He has announced a dedicated confidential national mental health support service for NHS doctors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired-gov.net/wg/news.nsf/articles/NHS+to+prioritise+doctors+mental+health+08102018091500?open|title=Better NHS support for NHS doctors' wellbeing.}}</ref>\n\nWhile supporting expanded health training opportunities for UK workers, he has backed ongoing selective international recruitment in the NHS. In October 2015 speaking to the [[Institute of Directors]] at the Albert Hall he queried why ballet dancers but not nurses were on the [[Home Office]]'s 'shortage occupation list.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2015/10/directors-convention/|title=NHS England \u00bb Simon Stevens speech to Institute of Directors Annual Convention|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> A week later the government added nurses to the list.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/nhs/11933399/Overseas-NHS-nurses-Restrictions-lifted-amid-widespread-shortages.html|title=Overseas NHS nurses: Restrictions lifted amid widespread shortages|last=Donnelly|first=Laura|date=15 October 2015|access-date=26 January 2019|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> He also led the introduction of an NHS Workforce Race Equality Standard to track and improve the experience and fair treatment of Black, Asian and Minority Ethnic Staff across the health service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nursinginpractice.com/article/simon-stevens-calls-nhs-lead-social-revolution-race-equality|title=Simon Stevens calls for NHS to lead a 'social revolution' on race equality|website=www.nursinginpractice.com|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> Stevens supports a greater role for the voluntary sector and volunteering in the NHS, as a complement to the work of NHS staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drsarah.org.uk/diary/simon-stevens-chief-executive-nhs-england/1234|title=Dr Sarah Wollaston {{!}} Diary|website=www.drsarah.org.uk|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/dec/06/volunteers-hospitals-nhs-staff|title=How an army of volunteers could help win the fight for the NHS|last=Brindle|first=David|date=6 December 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nStevens has championed giving local communities more control over national budgets, including stronger 'Devo Manc' regional powers for [[Greater Manchester Combined Authority|Greater Manchester]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/greater-manchester-health-devolution-deal-11126036|title=Greater Manchester's groundbreaking \u00c2\u00a36bn devo health deal comes into force today|last=Williams|first=Jennifer|date=1 April 2016|work=Manchester Evening News|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> He has argued for the importance of social care.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/health-and-care/social-care/news/81704/nhs-chief-simon-stevens-calls-immediate-support|title=NHS chief Simon Stevens calls for 'immediate support' for social care|date=13 December 2016|website=PoliticsHome.com|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> In October 2018 he pledged up to \u00a350 million for extra NHS support for the community affected by the Grenfell Tower fire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/nhs-pledges-up-to-50-million-to-screen-grenfell-survivors-for-smoke-inhalation-a3957811.html|title=NHS pledges \u00c2\u00a350 million to give Grenfell survivors health screenings|date=9 October 2018|website=Evening Standard|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> The ''[[Local Government Chronicle]]'' ranked him the most powerful figure in local government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lgcplus.com/home/lgc-briefing/lgc100-what-the-list-says-about-the-sector/7022852.article|title=LGC100: What the list says about the sector|last=Dalton|first=Rachel|website=Local Government Chronicle|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Prevention and public health ===\nStevens argues that \"[[obesity]] is the new smoking\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/may/31/obesity-new-smoking-nhs-england-chief-executive|title=Obesity is 'the new smoking' says NHS England's chief executive|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=31 May 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/05/31/obesityhas-become-new-smoking-will-fuel-weight-related-cancers/|title=Obesity has become 'the new smoking' and will fuel weight-related cancers, head of NHS warns|last=Donnelly|first=Laura|date=31 May 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> and has pushed for greater NHS, family, business and government action to tackle it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/health-and-care/house/62885/simon-stevens-interview-tackling-obesity-not-just-health-issue|title=Simon Stevens interview: \"Tackling obesity is not just a health issue \u2013 it's an economic necessity\"|date=4 June 2015|website=PoliticsHome.com|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/jul/03/obesity-rivals-smoking-as-cause-of-cancer-uk-charity-warns|title=Obesity rivals smoking as cause of cancer, UK charity warns|last=Boseley|first=Sarah|date=3 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> Stevens initiated NHS England's work with local authorities and developers to 'design in' health promoting built environments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/8a8779d0-def1-11e5-b072-006d8d362ba3|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2016/03/hlthy-new-towns/|title=NHS England \u00bb NHS Chief announces plan to support ten healthy new towns|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> These are now designated 'NHS healthy new towns'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/ourwork/innovation/healthy-new-towns/|title=NHS England \u00bb Healthy New Towns|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-nhs-plan-to-make-your-town-healthier-and-happier-s0sxqrxwd |title=The NHS plan to make your town healthier and happier |last=Smit |first=Josephine |date=1 September 2019|access-date=6 October 2019 |newspaper=The Times |location= London }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kingsfund.org.uk/sites/default/files/2019-09/Creating_healthy_places_pdf.pdf|title=Creating Healthy Places|last=|first=|date=|website=Kings Fund|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He launched the obesity-reducing NHS Diabetes Prevention Programme<ref>{{Cite press release |url= https://www.diabetes.org.uk/about_us/news/major-drive-to-prevent-illness-with-launch-of-national-type-2-prevention-drive-|title=Major drive to prevent illness with launch of national Type 2 prevention programme |publisher=Diabetes UK |access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> and later backed its national expansion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.personneltoday.com/hr/nhs-to-expand-diabetes-prevention-programme-nationwide/|title=NHS to expand Diabetes Prevention Programme nationwide|last=Webber|first=Ashleigh|date=6 December 2018|website=Personnel Today|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> He has championed NHS work to cut sugary drinks and junk food from hospitals,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2018-06-30/nhs-cuts-10-million-spoonfuls-of-sugar-from-hospital-drinks-sales/|title=NHS cuts 10 million spoonfuls of sugar from hospital drinks sales|website=ITV News|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> and suggested there should be a national [[Sugary drink tax|sugar tax]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nhs-chief-threatens-food-companies-over-sugar-w2mm8lwtvfj|title=NHS chief threatens food companies over sugar|last=Thomson|first=Chris Smyth, Rachel Sylvester and Alice|date=3 June 2015|work=The Times|access-date=6 October 2019 |location= London}}</ref> In March 2016 Chancellor [[George Osborne]] announced a tax on sugary drinks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-35340752|title=NHS England 'to impose 20% sugar tax' in hospital cafes|date=18 January 2016|accessdate=18 April 2016|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nHe has drawn attention to the growing problem of [[gambling addiction]]s, and the predominance of sports-related gambling promotions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/sep/05/premier-league-betting-sponsors-ignore-plight-of-uk-gambling-addicts|title=Premier League betting sponsors 'ignore plight of UK gambling addicts'|last=Campbell|first=Denis|date=5 September 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sbcnews.co.uk/retail/2018/09/07/gambleaware-backs-nhs-criticism-of-betting-footballs-failure-to-tackle-problem-gambling/|title=GambleAware backs NHS criticism of betting & football's failure to tackle problem gambling|date=7 September 2018|website=SBC News |access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> The NHS has opened new specialist clinics which Stevens argued the industry should contribute to funding.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} Shortly after Stevens' criticism, the six largest gambling companies announced a tenfold increase in their industry contributions to services for people affected by gambling.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-48834683 |title=Gambling firms pledge \u00a360m to help addicts|date=2 July 2019|access-date=6 October 2019 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nStevens has drawn attention to online sources of misinformation about [[Vaccine Safety Datalink|vaccine safety]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/02/health/vaccination-deniers-social-media-gbr-intl/index.html |title=Vaccination deniers gaining 'traction' on social media, health chief warns |first=Rob |last=Picheta |date=2 March 2019 |website=CNN|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> He has noted that \"although nine in ten parents say they support vaccination half of them say that they have seen fake messages around vaccination on social media,\" and \"if parents are being told that their children shouldn\u2019t be vaccinated, it\u2019s as irresponsible as saying 'don\u2019t tell your children to look both ways before they cross the road on the way to school\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/anti-vaccination-fake-news-social-media-fuels-tripling-measles/|title=Anti-vaccination fake news on social media fuels tripling in measles cases, head of NHS says|last=Donnelly|first=Laura|date=25 June 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-47417966|title=Vaccine deniers gaining ground - NHS boss|date=1 March 2019|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> He called on social media sites to take action against misleading and untrue health claims.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/25/world/europe/children-measles-vaccine.html|title=Over 20 Million Children a Year Miss Out on First Dose of Measles Vaccine|last=Magra|first=Iliana|date=25 April 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-48039524|title=Measles baby's eyes 'were swollen shut' |work=BBC News |date=25 April 2019|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> Both Instagram<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.newscientist.com/article/2202447-instagram-is-attempting-to-crack-down-on-misinformation-about-vaccines/ |work=New Scientist |location= London |title=\nInstagram is attempting to crack down on misinformation about vaccines |date=10 May 2019 |access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> and Facebook<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/07/02/facebook-announces-crackdown-misleading-health-content/|title=Facebook announces crackdown on misleading health content|date=2 July 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> subsequently agreed to do so.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/aug/30/sharp-rise-in-measles-in-england-amid-fears-over-anti-vaxxers |title=Sharp rise in measles in England amid fears over 'anti-vaxxers'|first=Denis |last=Campbell|date=30 August 2019 |work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn response to rising knife crime, Stevens appointed trauma surgeon Martin Griffith to lead the NHS' work on violence reduction,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/surgeon-martin-griffiths-to-lead-nhs-fight-against-deadly-knife-crime-kznl3k5mh|title=Surgeon Martin Griffiths to lead NHS fight against deadly knife crime |first1=Tom |last1=Whipple |first2=John |last2=Simpson|date=20 June 2019|work=The Times|access-date=6 October 2019 |location= London }}</ref> educating children about the consequences of stabbings, alongside youth workers helping victims of gang crime while they are still being treated in hospital to help break the cycle of violence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/06/19/nhs-send-surgeons-schools-combat-knife-crime-epidemic/|title=NHS to send surgeons into schools to combat knife crime epidemic|last=Donnelly|first=Laura|date=19 June 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=6 October 2019 |location= London}}</ref>\n\nOn [[climate change]], he told the Royal Society of Medicine that \"We have over 2,000 GP surgeries and hospitals located in zones with poisonous air [and] Public Health England estimates [air pollution will lead to] about 2.4 million cases of avoidable illness between now and 2035. We\u2019ve already got more respiratory problems than the rest of Europe and according to the Royal College of Physicians up to 40,000 deaths may be associated with this pollution.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.hsj.co.uk/policy-and-regulation/stevens-nhs-must-take-more-responsibility-for-tackling-climate-change/7025155.article|title=Stevens: NHS must take more responsibility for tackling climate change |last=Mclellan |first=Alastair |date=28 May 2019 |website=Health Service Journal |access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> For these reasons Stevens argues that \"The [[Global warming|climate emergency]] is a health emergency, and we, the NHS, as the single biggest organisation across this country are both part of the solution and part of the problem. We are 40% of public sector emissions, and although we have reduced our carbon footprint by around a fifth over the past decade, we\u2019ve got to make major changes if we\u2019re going to help this country become carbon net neutral.\u201d<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Iacobucci|first=Gareth|date=5 September 2019|title=NHS to step up efforts to tackle \"health emergency\" of climate change|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/366/bmj.l5458|journal=BMJ|language=en|volume=366|pages=l5458|doi=10.1136/bmj.l5458|issn=0959-8138|pmid=31488398}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/air-pollution-child-life-expectancy-birmingham-a8992456.html|title=Air pollution cuts up to seven months off child life expectancy in Birmingham|date=8 July 2019|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe has also argued that the NHS \u2013 as the largest employer in Britain \u2013 is an 'anchor institution' in many local communities, and so needs to \"get more creative in developing staffing and clinical models that will enable us to sustain services and consider second and third order effects in terms of jobs and economic impact and social cohesion\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/policy-and-regulation/stevens-nhs-must-take-more-responsibility-for-tackling-climate-change/7025155.article|title=Stevens: NHS must take more responsibility for tackling climate change|last=Mclellan|first=Alastair|website=Health Service Journal|language=en|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== NHS funding and Brexit ===\nStevens has argued that \"One of the problems with NHS funding over the last 70 years has been its volatility. So, we bounce off the banks between boom and bust and that makes it very hard to plan services.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/health-and-care/nhs/house/house-magazine/96377/simon-stevens-%E2%80%9C-nhs-has-enormous |title=Simon Stevens: Simon Stevens: \"The NHS has an enormous responsibility to be wise stewards of this additional investment\" |date=28 June 2018 |website=PoliticsHome.com |access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref> In November 2017 Stevens gave a high profile speech making the case for a return to NHS funding increases in line with historic norms and independently assessed requirements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fabnhsstuff.net/fab-stuff/simon-stevens-ceo-nhs-england-speech-nhs-providers-birmingham-november-8th-full|title=Simon Stevens, CEO, NHS England \u2013 Speech to NHS Providers, Birmingham, November 8th \u2013 in full |website=Fab NHS Stuff |access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C9478wsR3jw |title=Sky News live coverage of Simon Stevens speech at NHS Providers conference November 2017 |access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref> He did so against the backdrop of a Vote Leave poster which had promised \u00a3350 million a week for the health service and which, he said, the \"public want to see honoured\". His call was widely supported both inside the NHS<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rcseng.ac.uk/news-and-events/media-centre/press-releases/extra-funding-for-nhs/ |title=Royal College of Surgeons|date=8 November 2017 |access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rcgp.org.uk/about-us/news/2017/november/stevens-right-to-call-for-more-nhs-funding-says-rcgp.aspx|title=Royal College of GPs}}</ref> and outside it, ranging from Brexit-supporting Jacob Rees-Mogg{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} to the Remain-supporting general secretary of the TUC.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/nov/09/brexit-promise-350m-a-week-nhs-budget|title=Let's have that Brexit-promised \u00a3350m a week now \u2013 the NHS can't afford to wait |last=O'Grady |first=Frances |date=9 November 2017 |work=The Guardian|access-date=26 January 2019 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018 \u2013 just ahead of the NHS' 70th Anniversary \u2013 the Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] announced extra funding for the NHS worth an average real terms increase of 3.4% a year, reaching \u00a320.5 billion extra in 2023/24.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2018-06-16/nhs-to-get-extra-384-million-per-week-after-brexit-government-says/|title=NHS to get extra \u00c2\u00a3384 million per week after Brexit Government says|website=ITV News|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nStevens led the NHS' 70th anniversary celebrations,<ref>{{Citation|title=NHS success down to \"Brilliance\" of staff says Simon Stevens|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-8URoHHZkZ4|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> including giving the address on 5 July 2018 in the national service of thanksgiving at [[Westminster Abbey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/health/nhs-boss-leads-special-service-at-westminster-abbey-to-celebrate-its-70-years-a3880506.html|title=NHS boss leads special service at Westminster Abbey to celebrate its 70 years|date=5 July 2018|website=Evening Standard|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2018/07/simon-stevens-nhs-70-address-to-westminster-abbey/|title=NHS England \u00bb Simon Stevens' NHS70 address to Westminster Abbey|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.westminster-abbey.org/abbey-news/westminster-abbey-celebrates-70th-anniversary-of-the-nhs/|title=Westminster Abbey celebrates 70th anniversary of the NHS|website=Westminster Abbey|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.westminster-abbey.org/media/8950/nhs-70th-service.pdf|title=Order of Service for Westminster Abbey NHS 70th Anniversary}}</ref>\n\n=== NHS Long Term Plan ===\nOn 7 January 2019 Stevens launched<ref>{{Citation|last=NHS England|title=NHS England Chief Executive Simon Stevens launches the NHS Long Term Plan|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dWFs70mcilU|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> the [https://www.longtermplan.nhs.uk NHS Long Term Plan], drawn up with patient groups and NHS clinicians. It set out how the NHS will use its extra funding to redesign care and improve outcomes over the decade ahead.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/jan/07/what-is-the-nhs-long-term-plan-and-can-it-achieve-its-aims|title=What is the NHS long-term plan and can it achieve its aims?|last=Boseley|first=Sarah|date=7 January 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The Prime Minister spoke at the launch giving government backing to the plan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/pm-speech-at-nhs-plan-launch-7-january-2019|title=PM speech at NHS plan launch: 7 January 2019|website=GOV.UK|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn drawing up the NHS Long Term Plan, NHS England was also asked by the cross-party House of Commons Health and Social Care Committee, and by the Prime Minister, to make recommendations on possible changes to health legislation. Stevens came forward with proposals to substantially amend the government\u2019s previous [[Health and Social Care Act 2012|2012 legislation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-46827981|title=Are Lansley's NHS reforms being binned?|last=Triggle|first=Nick|date=11 January 2019|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/feb/28/scrap-laws-driving-privatisation-of-health-service-say-nhs-bosses|title=Scrap laws driving privatisation of health service, say NHS bosses|last=Campbell|first=|date=28 February 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/give-hospitals-freedom-to-work-together-says-nhs-chief-9h7gmwgtj|title=Give hospitals freedom to work together, says NHS chief|last=Smyth|first=Chris|date=27 September 2019|work=The Times|access-date=6 October 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> A wide range of stakeholders called for an NHS Long Term Plan including the Age UK, Macmillan Cancer, the British Red Cross, RCN, Unison, the Medical Royal Colleges, the Kings Fund, NHS Providers, the NHS Confederation, the Local Government Association, Alzheimers Society, British Heart Foundation, Diabetes UK, the Stroke Association and the Patients Association. This letter specifically called for the removal of Section 75 of the 2012 Health and Social Care Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhsconfed.org/-/media/Confederation/Files/Publications/Documents/Support-letter-NHS-legislation-proposals-FINAL.pdf|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The new government of Boris Johnson announced in the Queens Speech of 14 October 2019 that it would back the Long Term Plan, legislate for the \u00a320.5 billion real terms funding increase, and introduce legislation to give effect to the NHS's recommended legal changes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/839370/Queen_s_Speech_Lobby_Pack_2019_.pdf|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nStevens proposed - and NHS England then established - an 'NHS Assembly' to help steer implementation of the NHS Long Term Plan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2019/03/nhs-assembly-announced-to-help-deliver-the-long-term-plan/|title=NHS England \u00bb NHS Assembly announced to help deliver the Long Term Plan|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> It comprises a diverse range of stakeholders including national and local patients' groups, NHS staff and clinical experts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalhealthexecutive.com/Health-Care-News/wide-array-of-nhs-figures-named-as-the-new-nhs-assembly-announced|title=Wide array of NHS figures named as the new NHS Assembly announced|website=www.nationalhealthexecutive.com|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Research and innovation ===\nStevens led action to stop NHS funding of homeopathy, on the grounds that \"There is no robust evidence to support homeopathy, which is at best a placebo and a misuse of scarce NHS funds.\" NHS England was then sued by the British Homeopathic Association who argued that Stevens\u2019 criticisms, including on the BBC Radio Today programme, prejudged its public consultation. The High Court dismissed the BHA challenge, and backed NHS England.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/2018/06/05/high-court-backs-nhs-decision-stop-funding-homeopathy/|title=High Court backs NHS decision to stop funding homeopathy|last=Donnelly|first=Laura|date=5 June 2018|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=26 January 2019|last2=Association|first2=Press|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=THE HONOURABLE MR JUSTICE SUPPERSTONE|title=British Homeopathic Association, R (On the Application Of) v National Health Service Commissioning Board [2018] EWHC 1359 (Admin)|date=5 June 2018|url=http://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2018/1359.html|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nhs-demands-legal-costs-from-failed-homeopathy-challenge-sm80w8kjp|title=NHS demands legal costs from failed homeopathy challenge|last=Smyth|first=Chris|date=31 July 2018|work=The Times|access-date=26 January 2019|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nSpeaking at the [[World Economic Forum]] he launched the first wave of NHS Innovation Test Beds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalhealth.net/2016/01/stevens-launches-innovation-test-beds/|title=Stevens launches innovation 'test beds'|date=22 January 2016|website=Digital Health|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://medicinegov.org/nhs-open-to-global-innovation-healthcare-leaders-launch-search-for-best-new-ideas-from-around-the-world/|title=NHS open to global innovation: healthcare leaders launch search for best new ideas from around the world {{!}}|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> He supports digital hubs<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalhealth.net/2017/09/nhs-england-to-establish-new-digital-innovation-hubs/|title=NHS England to establish new regional Digital Innovation Hubs|date=12 September 2017|website=Digital Health|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> and introduced a new NHS innovation payment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2016/06/treatment-innovations/|title=NHS England \u00bb NHS Chief launches new fast track funding so NHS patients get treatment innovations faster|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> NHS England funds [[Academic Health Science Networks]], and Stevens supported the [[Accelerated Access Review]] arguing:\n\n\"As a nation we need to pursue three goals simultaneously. First, we must actively support new discovery and further development of innovative treatments and care. Second, we have no choice other than to drive value and affordability across the NHS if we're going to create headroom for faster and wider uptake of important new patient treatments. And third, in the run-up to Brexit we need not only to secure - but  enhance - our vibrant and globally successful UK life sciences sector.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/565072/AAR_final.pdf|title=Accelerated Access Review}}</ref>\n\nHe has pushed to deploy AI and Machine Learning in the NHS<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bma.org.uk/news/2017/september/artificial-intelligence-will-be-adopted-says-nhs-england|title=BMA - Artificial intelligence will be adopted, says NHS England|website=www.bma.org.uk|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/hospitals-robots-ai-replace-humans-nhs-simon-stevens-8dhztxtlc|title=Hospitals to get extra cash for using robots and AI to replace humans|last=Aldrick|first=Philip|date=6 June 2019|work=The Times|access-date=6 October 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> and NHS England will be hosting a new \u00a3250 million NHS AI Lab.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/08/uk-government-pledges-303-million-ai-project-for-healthcare.html|title=UK government pledges $303 million for A.I. project to tackle cancer, dementia and heart disease|last=Frangoul|first=Anmar|date=8 August 2019|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nStevens has actively promoted [[genomics]], and cell and gene therapies on the NHS.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/apr/26/nhs-car-t-game-changing-cancer-treatment-immune-therapy|title=NHS preparing to offer 'game-changing' cancer treatment|last=Boseley|first=Sarah|date=26 April 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 January 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/new-cancer-weapon-to-be-fast-tracked-into-hospitals-7dggrqdd5|title=New 'tumour-agnostic' cancer drugs to be fast\u2011tracked into hospitals|last=Whipple|first=Tom|date=19 June 2019|work=The Times|access-date=6 October 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2019/06/fast-track-game-changing-cancer-drugs/|title=NHS England \u00bb NHS prepares to fast-track 'game changing' cancer drugs that target genetic mutations|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/sep/04/one-off-injection-will-save-children-from-inherited-blindness|title=One-off injection will save children from inherited blindness|last=Boseley|first=Sarah|date=4 September 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In Autumn 2018 he announced that the NHS had become the first health service in Europe to negotiate approvals for newly licensed breakthrough [[CAR-T]] cancer therapies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/810e6aaa-b048-11e8-8d14-6f049d06439c|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/cancer-nhs-lymphoma-treatment-health-therapy-a8569441.html|title=NHS strikes deal for cutting edge cancer treatment for adults with lymphoma|date=5 October 2018|website=The Independent|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nStevens is critical of [[homeopathy]], which he maintains is \"fundamentally flawed\". Stevens does not want the [[Society of Homeopaths]] to be reaccredited. Stevens stated: \"This is a vital issue at a time when there is a rise of mis-information about vaccines - some of which is apparently promoted by homeopaths - and which poses a significant danger to human health.\" Stevens added: \"Anything that gives homeopathy a veneer of credibility risks chancers being able to con more people into parting with their hard-earned cash in return for bogus treatments which at best do nothing, and at worst can be potentially dangerous,\" he stated.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/oct/28/head-nhs-voices-serious-concerns-about-homeopathy-simon-stevens |title=Head of NHS voices 'serious concerns' about homeopathy |work=The Guardian |date=28 October 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-50207231 |title=Health bosses' 'serious concerns' over homeopathy |work=BBC News |date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Other activities and awards ==\nStevens was a Visiting Professor at the [[London School of Economics]] from 2004 to 2008, and is an Honorary Fellow of [[Balliol College, University of Oxford]].\n\nHe was awarded an Honorary Doctorate by the [[University of Birmingham]] in 2015, and is also an Honorary Fellow of the [[Royal College of General Practitioners]].\n\nSince becoming NHS England CEO he has given lectures and speeches at the universities of Oxford, Cambridge, Durham, Exeter, London, Birmingham, York, Manchester, Southampton, Newcastle, and previously at Harvard, Yale, and NYU.\n\nHe is regularly interviewed on the [[BBC]], [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], [[Sky News]], ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' and ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|The Today Programme]]'', as well as ''[[The Andrew Marr Show]]''. He has also appeared on ''[[Jeremy Vine (TV programme)|Jeremy Vine]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/p026f1yn|title=Jeremy Vine - Simon Stevens: What Makes Us Human? - BBC Sounds|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> ''[[BBC Breakfast]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BBCBreakfast/status/1082198179427295232|title=Today @NHSEngland will publish its 10-year plan, which will add an extra \u00a320bn per year by 2023. Chief Executive Simon Stevens told #BBCBreakfast what the future of this plan looks like. #NHSEngland #healthcare #fundingpic.twitter.com/FG1j6Bs5In|date=7 January 2019|website=@BBCBreakfast|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> ''[[Any Questions?]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06py0lm|title=David Gauke MP, Bronwen Maddox, John McDonnell MP, Simon Stevens|website=BBC Any Questions|accessdate=7 December 2015}}</ref> and ''[[The One Show]]''.\n\nSince 2013 Stevens has served on the board of directors of the [[Commonwealth Fund]] of New York<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.harknessfellows.org.uk/all-harkness-stories/1990s/simon-stevens|title=Simon Stevens|date=25 May 2018|website=Harkness Fellows|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> and is a member of its Investment Committee.\n\nHe lists his hobbies as family, offshore sailing, books and 'cooking without recipes'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.director.co.uk/leadership-lessons-simon-stevens-nhs/|title=The leadership lessons of NHS England's Simon Stevens \u2013 Director|date=20 August 2019|website=Director Magazine|language=en-GB|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{NHS England}}\n{{British special advisers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stevens, Simon}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Strathclyde]]\n[[Category:People from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:Chief Executives of the National Health Service]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Lambeth]]\n[[Category:British special advisers]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Oxford Union]]\n[[Category:English healthcare chief executives]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2014}} \n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = Sir \n| name = Simon Stevens\n| image = Simon Stevens NHS 225x300.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| office = Chief Executive of [[NHS England]]\n| term_start = 1 April 2014\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[David Nicholson (civil servant)|Sir David Nicholson]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Lambeth London Borough Council|Lambeth Borough Councillor]] for Angell Ward\n| term_start1 = 7 May 1998\n| term_end1 = 2 May 2002\n| predecessor1 = \n| successor1 = \n| birth_date = <!--{{birth date and age|| | |df=y}}-->\n| birth_place = [[Shard End]], [[Birmingham]], England\n| birth_name =\n| nationality = \n| relations = \n| spouse = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Balliol College, Oxford]]<br>[[University of Strathclyde]]\n| occupation = \n| religion = \n| website = \n}}\n'''Sir Simon Laurence Stevens''' (born 4 August 1966) is a British [[Health management|health manager]] and public policy analyst. His appointment<ref>{{Cite press release |url= http://www.england.nhs.uk/2013/10/24/simon-stevens-appoint/|title=Simon Stevens Appointed as new Chief Executive of NHS England |publisher=NHS England |date=24 October 2013 |access-date=19 March 2016}}</ref> as the eighth [[Chief Executives of the NHS|Chief Executive]] of the [[NHS England|National Health Service in England]] with effect from 1 April 2014 was announced in October 2013, succeeding [[David Nicholson (civil servant)|David Nicholson]]. He was said by the ''[[Health Service Journal]]'' in December 2013 to be the second most powerful person in the English NHS, even before he took up his appointment.<ref>{{cite news|title=HSJ100 2013 The annual list of the most influential people in health|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/leadership/hsj-100/|accessdate=14 December 2013|newspaper=Health Service Journal|date=11 December 2013}}</ref> He has stayed top of their list of the most influential people in health ever since.<ref>{{cite news |title=HSJ100 full list: Stevens tops table for fifth year |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/hsj100/hsj100-full-list-stevens-tops-table-for-fifth-year/7023990.article |accessdate=22 January 2019 |work=Health Service Journal |date=13 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSimon Stevens was born in [[Birmingham]], England,<ref name=\"whoswho2017bio\">{{cite web|title=STEVENS, Simon Laurence|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U272409|website=Who's Who 2017|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> the son of a Baptist minister and a university administrator.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boseley|first=Sarah|date=21 June 2014|title=Simon Stevens: visionary Chief Executive of NHS England|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(14)61019-9/abstract|journal=The Lancet |volume=383 |issue=9935 |page=2117 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(14)61019-9|issn=0140-6736|pmid=24953466}}</ref> He was educated at a state comprehensive, [[St. Bartholomew's School]], and won a scholarship to [[Balliol College, Oxford]] University, where he was elected president of the [[Oxford Union]]. His friends at Balliol reportedly ranged from [[Extinction Rebellion]]'s [[Rupert Read]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08byj3g|title=BBC Radio 4 - Profile, Simon Stevens|website=BBC |access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref> to [[Boris Johnson]] who credited Stevens with Johnson's own election as Oxford Union president.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/25/boris-johnson-filmed-telling-tory-members-nhs-needs-reform |title=Boris Johnson filmed telling Tory members NHS 'needs reform' |last=Mason |first=Rowena |date=25 June 2019 |work=The Guardian |location= London |access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/how-a-young-boris-johnson-bonded-with-nhs-chief-simon-stevens-jc28c080r|title=How a young Boris Johnson bonded with NHS chief Simon Stevens |last=Courea|first=Eleni|date=6 August 2019|work=The Times|access-date=6 October 2019 |location= London}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/08/07/future-pm-boris-johnson-nhs-boss-simon-stevens-formed-unlikely/|title=How the future PM, Boris Johnson, and NHS boss, Simon Stevens, formed an unlikely bond at Oxford |last=Bird |first=Steve |date=7 August 2019 |work=The Telegraph |location= London |access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"kuper\">{{cite news |last1=Kuper |first1=Simon |title=How Oxford university shaped Brexit \u2014 and Britain's next prime minister |url=https://www.ft.com/content/85fc694c-9222-11e9-b7ea-60e35ef678d2 |accessdate=21 June 2019 |work=Financial Times |location= London |date=21 June 2019}}</ref> Stevens later received an MBA from the [[University of Strathclyde]], Glasgow and was a [[Harkness Fellowship|Harkness Fellow]] at [[Columbia University]], New York. His wife, Maggie, is a public health specialist from New York City. Their son was born on Christmas Day 2003 at [[St Thomas' Hospital]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/oct/24/simon-stevens-interview|title=The NHS is a social movement|last=|first=|date=24 October 2014|work=|accessdate=25 October 2014|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> and their daughter in 2008.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/10864008/Simon-Stevens-The-NHS-is-at-a-defining-moment.html |title=Simon Stevens: 'The NHS is at a defining moment' |last=Donnelly |first=Laura |date=29 May 2014 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==NHS==\nAfter university Stevens first worked in [[Guyana]],<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Simon Stevens: visionary Chief Executive of NHS England|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(14)61019-9/fulltext|journal=The Lancet|volume=383|page=2117|via=|pmid=24953466|year=2014|last1=Boseley|first1=S.|issue=9935|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(14)61019-9}}</ref> and then from 1988 to 1997 as a healthcare manager in the UK and internationally. He started his NHS career on the [http://www.nhsgraduates.co.uk NHS Graduate Management Training Scheme] at Shotley Bridge General Hospital, the largest employer in [[Consett]], County Durham, after the closure of the [[Consett Steel Works|steel works]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/nhs-chief-simon-stevens-goes-6905643 |title=NHS chief Simon Stevens goes back to North East roots |last=Rae |first=Helen |date=2 April 2014 |newspaper=Evening Chronicle |location= Newcastle |access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release |url= https://www.england.nhs.uk/2014/04/simon-stevens-speech/ |date=1 April 2014 |publisher=NHS England |title=Full text of Simon Stevens' speech |website=www.england.nhs.uk |access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref>  After a spell in [[Republic of the Congo|Congo]] and [[Malawi]], he became general manager for [http://www.mark-davis-photography.com/explore/st-georges-hospital-morpeth/ a large NHS psychiatric hospital outside Newcastle-upon-Tyne], and ran community mental health services for North Tyneside and Northumberland. He was then appointed group manager of [[Guy's and St Thomas' NHS Foundation Trust|Guy's and St Thomas' hospitals]] in London<ref>{{cite press release |url= https://www.guysandstthomas.nhs.uk/news-and-events/2015-news/november/20151104-simon-stevens-speaks-at-veterans-agm.aspx |title=Simon Stevens at Guys and St Thomas' |date=4 November 2015 |publisher=Guys and St Thomas' NHS Foundation Trust }}</ref> before moving to [[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene|New York City Health Department]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-272409|title=Stevens, Simon Laurence, (born 4 Aug. 1966), Chief Executive, NHS England, since 2014 {{!}} WHO'S WHO & WHO WAS WHO|website=www.ukwhoswho.com|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U272409|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Government ==\nIn 1997 he was appointed policy adviser to two successive [[Secretaries of State for Health]] ([[Frank Dobson]] and [[Alan Milburn]]) at the UK [[Department of Health and Social Care|Department of Health]]. From 2001 to 2004 he was the Government's health policy adviser in the [[Number 10 Policy Unit]] to [[Tony Blair]] at [[10 Downing Street]]. Stevens was a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] councillor for [[Brixton]], in the [[London Borough of Lambeth]] 1998\u20132002. He was closely associated with the development of the [[NHS Plan 2000]].\n\n== UnitedHealth ==\nFrom 2004 to 2014 Stevens was a senior executive at [https://www.unitedhealthgroup.com UnitedHealth Group]. Initially appointed president of UnitedHealth Europe, he became CEO of UnitedHealthcare's $30 billion Medicare business, and then corporate Executive Vice President and president of its global health businesses spanning the Americas, Europe, Asia, and Africa. He also was a director of Brazil's largest hospital group [http://www.amil.com.br AMIL].\n\nHe was instrumental in establishing a non-profit institute to publish information about inefficiency in the US health system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.healthcostinstitute.org|title=Health Care Cost Institute}}</ref> These data proved that contrary to prior research mainly using Medicare data, cost differences in the working age population were a result not mainly because of differences in service utilisation but also because of market pricing power by hospitals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/12/15/upshot/the-best-places-for-better-cheaper-health-care-arent-what-experts-thought.html,%20https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/12/15/upshot/the-best-places-for-better-cheaper-health-care-arent-what-experts-thought.html|title=The Experts Were Wrong About the Best Places for Better and Cheaper Health Care |last=Quealy |first=Kevin|date=15 December 2015 |work=The New York Times|access-date=6 October 2019|last2=Sanger-Katz|first2=Margot }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.modernhealthcare.com/article/20190204/NEWS/190209984/hospital-price-growth-driving-healthcare-spending |title=Hospital price growth driving healthcare spending |date=4 February 2019|website=Modern Healthcare |access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe also served on the boards of various non-profits, including the [[Minnesota Historical Society]]; the [[Minnesota Opera]]; and the [[Medicare Rights Center]] (New York), as well as the [[King's Fund]] and the [[Nuffield Trust]].\n\n==Chief executive of NHS England==\n\nAs the [[Chief Executives of the NHS|NHS England CEO]], he is directly accountable to Parliament for management of \u00a3120 billion of annual NHS funding. He frequently gives evidence to the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]], the House of Commons Health and Social Care Committee, and other Parliamentary committees. He has used the statutory independence of NHS England to speak openly about NHS funding and reform.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/sites/default/files/publications/World%27s%20Biggest%20Quango%20NHS%20England%20web.pdf|title=The first five years of NHS England|last=Timmins|first=Nicholas}}</ref> In January 2019 he welcomed new figures from the [[Office for National Statistics]] showing that NHS productivity in England has been rising at 3%, treble the performance of the overall UK economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2019/01/skill-and-dedication-of-nhs-staff-praised-as-health-service-productivity-outstrips-the-rest-of-the-economy/|title=NHS England \u00bb Skill and dedication of NHS staff praised as health service productivity outstrips the rest of the economy|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pharmafield.co.uk/pharma_news/nhs-staff-praised-as-productivity-grows/|title=NHS staff praised as productivity grows|last=Schofield|first=Amy|date=23 April 2019 |website=Pharmafield |access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn his return to the NHS, ''The Guardian'' reported one health expert as saying \"He's coming back to a pay cut [and] the mother of all messes\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/jan/18/simon-stevens-trying-save-nhs-from-mother-of-messes|title=Simon Stevens \u2013 trying to steer the NHS through tumultuous times|last=|first=|date=|work=The Guardian|access-date=}}</ref> Stevens' own assessment was that \"For the NHS the stakes have never been higher. The global recession has meant the NHS facing its most sustained budget crunch in its history. Service pressures are intensifying, and longstanding problems are not going to disappear overnight.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2014/04/simon-stevens-speech/|title=NHS England \u00bb Full text of Simon Stevens' speech|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> Stevens said his aim was to '''\"'''Think like a patient, act like a taxpayer.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/jan/18/simon-stevens-trying-save-nhs-from-mother-of-messes |title=Simon Stevens: trying to steer the NHS through tumultuous times |last=Johnson |first=Paul |date=18 January 2016 |work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019 |location= London }}</ref> As of 2015, Stevens was paid a salary of between \u00a3190,000 and \u00a3194,999 by NHS England<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/492289/150K_senior_salaries.csv/preview|title=Senior officials 'high earners' salaries as at 30 September 2015 \u2013 GOV.UK|date=17 December 2015|website=www.gov.uk|access-date=13 March 2016}}</ref> and each year he has opted for a voluntary \u00a320,000 pay cut.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/nhs/10400660/Blair-advisor-Simon-Stevens-appointed-new-NHS-chief-executive.html|title=Blair advisor Simon Stevens appointed new NHS chief executive|last=Donnelly|first=Laura|date=23 October 2013|access-date=26 January 2019|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> According to [[Fraser Nelson]], hiring Stevens back to run NHS England was one of the cleverest moves that [[David Cameron]] made because he \"knows more about NHS problems and market solutions than any man alive\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/fraser-nelson/2014/10/the-nhs-wales-disaster-vindicates-tony-blair-not-david-cameron/|title=The NHS Wales disaster vindicates Tony Blair, not David Cameron|date=24 October 2014|accessdate=25 October 2014|publisher=The Spectator}}</ref> During the 2019 General Election campaign while the Labour Party said they would generally not comment on the appointments of public officials, they stated they have a \"good relationship with Simon Stevens and respect him.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.hsj.co.uk/leadership/labour-voices-respect-for-nhs-chief-simon-stevens/7026365.article |title=Labour voices 'respect' for NHS chief Simon Stevens |date=13 November 2019 |last=Dunhill |first=Lawrence|website=Health Service Journal |access-date=26 December 2019}}</ref> In March 2019 it was announced Stevens would also lead the hospital regulator, NHS Improvement, effectively merging it into NHS England.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.onmedica.com/newsArticle.aspx?id=2caa55b9-7ab2-47f8-b18a-4fff654b6a94|title=OnMedica - News - NHS Improvement set to merge with NHS England|website=www.onmedica.com|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nStevens was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the [[2020 New Year Honours]] for services to the NHS.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62866|supp=y|page=N2|date=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== NHS Five Year Forward View ===\nHe was responsible for the [[Five Year Forward View]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=71HWJXufqlM|title=NHS Five Year Forward View video}}</ref> produced by NHS England in October 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kingsfund.org.uk/blog/2014/10/nhs-five-year-forward-view-man-matters-more-plan|title=The NHS five year forward view: the man matters more than the plan|date=27 October 2014|website=The King's Fund|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> This marked the beginning of a major shift in how NHS care is delivered, in contrast to NHS policy since 1991. Instead care is increasingly being redesigned to achieve what Stevens labelled the \"triple integration\" of primary and specialist care, physical and mental health services, and NHS and social care.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2014/06/simon-stevens-speech-confed/|title=NHS England \u00bb Speech by Simon Stevens, CEO NHS England, to the NHS Confederation Annual Conference 2014|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2015/05/fit-for-future/|title=NHS England \u00bb Simon Stevens call for bold action to make NHS fit for the future|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> He has however recently challenged the longstanding assumption that this will mean there is a need for fewer hospital beds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/jun/19/hospital-bed-cutbacks-have-gone-too-far-nhs-england-boss-simon-stevens-says|title=Hospital bed cutbacks have gone too far, NHS England boss says|last=Campbell |first=Denis|date=19 June 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019 |location= London }}</ref>\n\nStevens has also prioritised the modernisation of NHS primary care,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/gpfv.pdf|title=The NHS GP Forward View}}</ref> mental health and cancer care<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/cancer/|title=NHS England \u00bb Cancer|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> having commissioned an independent national taskforce led by Sir Harpal Kumar the chief executive of Cancer Research UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cancerresearchuk.org/about-us/cancer-strategy-in-england|title=Cancer Strategy in England|date=10 March 2017|website=Cancer Research UK|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> Breast cancer deaths have subsequently fallen faster than in other large European countries and outcomes are estimated to have caught up with or surpassed the European average.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/mar/19/uk-breast-cancer-death-rates-falling-fastest-in-big-six-of-europe|title=UK breast cancer death rates falling fastest in 'big six' of Europe|last=Campbell|first=Denis|date=19 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> In 2015 he commissioned the independent [https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Mental-Health-Taskforce-FYFV-final.pdf Five Year Forward View for mental health] chaired by Paul Farmer the head of MIND.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mind.org.uk/news-campaigns/news/paul-farmer-to-chair-mental-health-taskforce/#.XExlMi2cZyo |title=Paul Farmer to chair mental health taskforce |work=Mind.org.uk |date=2015-03-25}}</ref> He subsequently directed that each year local mental health spending must rise faster than overall NHS funding growth.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/health-44651742|title=Mental health services need 'major ramp up' |work=BBC News |date=29 June 2018|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> Given increasing concerns about young people\u2019s mental health and eating disorders, he voiced concern on the BBC's Andrew Marr show about cosmetic surgery adverts during ITV's ''[[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 4)|Love Island]]'' series.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} Shortly after, ITV's chief executive agreed to reconsider the ads,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2018/jul/25/itv-to-review-use-of-plastic-surgery-and-diet-ads-during-love-island|title=ITV to review use of plastic surgery and diet ads during Love Island|last=Waterson|first=Jim|date=25 July 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019|last2=Sweney|first2=Mark |location= London}}</ref> and the Advertising Standards Authority went on to ban them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/oct/17/breast-enlargement-ads-shown-during-love-island-banned-by-asa|title=Breast enlargement ads shown during Love Island banned by ASA|last=Rawlinson|first=Kevin|date=16 October 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> He\u00a0has suggested that social media companies might be asked to contribute to funding improved mental health support for young people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/10/10/facebook-instagram-should-pay-mental-health-levy-nhs-damage/|title=Facebook should pay a 'mental health' levy for the damage it causes, says NHS boss |last=Donnelly |first=Laura|date=10 October 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=27 January 2019 |location= London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sbcnews.co.uk/retail/2018/09/07/gambleaware-backs-nhs-criticism-of-betting-footballs-failure-to-tackle-problem-gambling/|title=GambleAware backs NHS criticism of betting & football's failure to tackle problem gambling|date=7 September 2018|website=SBC News|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> He has announced a dedicated confidential national mental health support service for NHS doctors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired-gov.net/wg/news.nsf/articles/NHS+to+prioritise+doctors+mental+health+08102018091500?open|title=Better NHS support for NHS doctors' wellbeing.}}</ref>\n\nWhile supporting expanded health training opportunities for UK workers, he has backed ongoing selective international recruitment in the NHS. In October 2015 speaking to the [[Institute of Directors]] at the Albert Hall he queried why ballet dancers but not nurses were on the [[Home Office]]'s 'shortage occupation list.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2015/10/directors-convention/|title=NHS England \u00bb Simon Stevens speech to Institute of Directors Annual Convention|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> A week later the government added nurses to the list.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/nhs/11933399/Overseas-NHS-nurses-Restrictions-lifted-amid-widespread-shortages.html|title=Overseas NHS nurses: Restrictions lifted amid widespread shortages|last=Donnelly|first=Laura|date=15 October 2015|access-date=26 January 2019|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> He also led the introduction of an NHS Workforce Race Equality Standard to track and improve the experience and fair treatment of Black, Asian and Minority Ethnic Staff across the health service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nursinginpractice.com/article/simon-stevens-calls-nhs-lead-social-revolution-race-equality|title=Simon Stevens calls for NHS to lead a 'social revolution' on race equality|website=www.nursinginpractice.com|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> Stevens supports a greater role for the voluntary sector and volunteering in the NHS, as a complement to the work of NHS staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drsarah.org.uk/diary/simon-stevens-chief-executive-nhs-england/1234|title=Dr Sarah Wollaston {{!}} Diary|website=www.drsarah.org.uk|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/dec/06/volunteers-hospitals-nhs-staff|title=How an army of volunteers could help win the fight for the NHS|last=Brindle|first=David|date=6 December 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nStevens has championed giving local communities more control over national budgets, including stronger 'Devo Manc' regional powers for [[Greater Manchester Combined Authority|Greater Manchester]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/greater-manchester-health-devolution-deal-11126036|title=Greater Manchester's groundbreaking \u00c2\u00a36bn devo health deal comes into force today|last=Williams|first=Jennifer|date=1 April 2016|work=Manchester Evening News|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> He has argued for the importance of social care.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/health-and-care/social-care/news/81704/nhs-chief-simon-stevens-calls-immediate-support|title=NHS chief Simon Stevens calls for 'immediate support' for social care|date=13 December 2016|website=PoliticsHome.com|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> In October 2018 he pledged up to \u00a350 million for extra NHS support for the community affected by the Grenfell Tower fire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/nhs-pledges-up-to-50-million-to-screen-grenfell-survivors-for-smoke-inhalation-a3957811.html|title=NHS pledges \u00c2\u00a350 million to give Grenfell survivors health screenings|date=9 October 2018|website=Evening Standard|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> The ''[[Local Government Chronicle]]'' ranked him the most powerful figure in local government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lgcplus.com/home/lgc-briefing/lgc100-what-the-list-says-about-the-sector/7022852.article|title=LGC100: What the list says about the sector|last=Dalton|first=Rachel|website=Local Government Chronicle|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Prevention and public health ===\nStevens argues that \"[[obesity]] is the new smoking\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/may/31/obesity-new-smoking-nhs-england-chief-executive|title=Obesity is 'the new smoking' says NHS England's chief executive|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=31 May 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/05/31/obesityhas-become-new-smoking-will-fuel-weight-related-cancers/|title=Obesity has become 'the new smoking' and will fuel weight-related cancers, head of NHS warns|last=Donnelly|first=Laura|date=31 May 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> and has pushed for greater NHS, family, business and government action to tackle it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/health-and-care/house/62885/simon-stevens-interview-tackling-obesity-not-just-health-issue|title=Simon Stevens interview: \"Tackling obesity is not just a health issue \u2013 it's an economic necessity\"|date=4 June 2015|website=PoliticsHome.com|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/jul/03/obesity-rivals-smoking-as-cause-of-cancer-uk-charity-warns|title=Obesity rivals smoking as cause of cancer, UK charity warns|last=Boseley|first=Sarah|date=3 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> Stevens initiated NHS England's work with local authorities and developers to 'design in' health promoting built environments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/8a8779d0-def1-11e5-b072-006d8d362ba3|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2016/03/hlthy-new-towns/|title=NHS England \u00bb NHS Chief announces plan to support ten healthy new towns|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> These are now designated 'NHS healthy new towns'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/ourwork/innovation/healthy-new-towns/|title=NHS England \u00bb Healthy New Towns|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-nhs-plan-to-make-your-town-healthier-and-happier-s0sxqrxwd |title=The NHS plan to make your town healthier and happier |last=Smit |first=Josephine |date=1 September 2019|access-date=6 October 2019 |newspaper=The Times |location= London }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kingsfund.org.uk/sites/default/files/2019-09/Creating_healthy_places_pdf.pdf|title=Creating Healthy Places|last=|first=|date=|website=Kings Fund|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He launched the obesity-reducing NHS Diabetes Prevention Programme<ref>{{Cite press release |url= https://www.diabetes.org.uk/about_us/news/major-drive-to-prevent-illness-with-launch-of-national-type-2-prevention-drive-|title=Major drive to prevent illness with launch of national Type 2 prevention programme |publisher=Diabetes UK |access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> and later backed its national expansion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.personneltoday.com/hr/nhs-to-expand-diabetes-prevention-programme-nationwide/|title=NHS to expand Diabetes Prevention Programme nationwide|last=Webber|first=Ashleigh|date=6 December 2018|website=Personnel Today|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> He has championed NHS work to cut sugary drinks and junk food from hospitals,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2018-06-30/nhs-cuts-10-million-spoonfuls-of-sugar-from-hospital-drinks-sales/|title=NHS cuts 10 million spoonfuls of sugar from hospital drinks sales|website=ITV News|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> and suggested there should be a national [[Sugary drink tax|sugar tax]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nhs-chief-threatens-food-companies-over-sugar-w2mm8lwtvfj|title=NHS chief threatens food companies over sugar|last=Thomson|first=Chris Smyth, Rachel Sylvester and Alice|date=3 June 2015|work=The Times|access-date=6 October 2019 |location= London}}</ref> In March 2016 Chancellor [[George Osborne]] announced a tax on sugary drinks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-35340752|title=NHS England 'to impose 20% sugar tax' in hospital cafes|date=18 January 2016|accessdate=18 April 2016|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nHe has drawn attention to the growing problem of [[gambling addiction]]s, and the predominance of sports-related gambling promotions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/sep/05/premier-league-betting-sponsors-ignore-plight-of-uk-gambling-addicts|title=Premier League betting sponsors 'ignore plight of UK gambling addicts'|last=Campbell|first=Denis|date=5 September 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sbcnews.co.uk/retail/2018/09/07/gambleaware-backs-nhs-criticism-of-betting-footballs-failure-to-tackle-problem-gambling/|title=GambleAware backs NHS criticism of betting & football's failure to tackle problem gambling|date=7 September 2018|website=SBC News |access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> The NHS has opened new specialist clinics which Stevens argued the industry should contribute to funding.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} Shortly after Stevens' criticism, the six largest gambling companies announced a tenfold increase in their industry contributions to services for people affected by gambling.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-48834683 |title=Gambling firms pledge \u00a360m to help addicts|date=2 July 2019|access-date=6 October 2019 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nStevens has drawn attention to online sources of misinformation about [[Vaccine Safety Datalink|vaccine safety]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/02/health/vaccination-deniers-social-media-gbr-intl/index.html |title=Vaccination deniers gaining 'traction' on social media, health chief warns |first=Rob |last=Picheta |date=2 March 2019 |website=CNN|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> He has noted that \"although nine in ten parents say they support vaccination half of them say that they have seen fake messages around vaccination on social media,\" and \"if parents are being told that their children shouldn\u2019t be vaccinated, it\u2019s as irresponsible as saying 'don\u2019t tell your children to look both ways before they cross the road on the way to school\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/anti-vaccination-fake-news-social-media-fuels-tripling-measles/|title=Anti-vaccination fake news on social media fuels tripling in measles cases, head of NHS says|last=Donnelly|first=Laura|date=25 June 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-47417966|title=Vaccine deniers gaining ground - NHS boss|date=1 March 2019|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> He called on social media sites to take action against misleading and untrue health claims.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/25/world/europe/children-measles-vaccine.html|title=Over 20 Million Children a Year Miss Out on First Dose of Measles Vaccine|last=Magra|first=Iliana|date=25 April 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-48039524|title=Measles baby's eyes 'were swollen shut' |work=BBC News |date=25 April 2019|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> Both Instagram<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.newscientist.com/article/2202447-instagram-is-attempting-to-crack-down-on-misinformation-about-vaccines/ |work=New Scientist |location= London |title=\nInstagram is attempting to crack down on misinformation about vaccines |date=10 May 2019 |access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> and Facebook<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/07/02/facebook-announces-crackdown-misleading-health-content/|title=Facebook announces crackdown on misleading health content|date=2 July 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> subsequently agreed to do so.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/aug/30/sharp-rise-in-measles-in-england-amid-fears-over-anti-vaxxers |title=Sharp rise in measles in England amid fears over 'anti-vaxxers'|first=Denis |last=Campbell|date=30 August 2019 |work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn response to rising knife crime, Stevens appointed trauma surgeon Martin Griffith to lead the NHS' work on violence reduction,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/surgeon-martin-griffiths-to-lead-nhs-fight-against-deadly-knife-crime-kznl3k5mh|title=Surgeon Martin Griffiths to lead NHS fight against deadly knife crime |first1=Tom |last1=Whipple |first2=John |last2=Simpson|date=20 June 2019|work=The Times|access-date=6 October 2019 |location= London }}</ref> educating children about the consequences of stabbings, alongside youth workers helping victims of gang crime while they are still being treated in hospital to help break the cycle of violence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/06/19/nhs-send-surgeons-schools-combat-knife-crime-epidemic/|title=NHS to send surgeons into schools to combat knife crime epidemic|last=Donnelly|first=Laura|date=19 June 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=6 October 2019 |location= London}}</ref>\n\nOn [[climate change]], he told the Royal Society of Medicine that \"We have over 2,000 GP surgeries and hospitals located in zones with poisonous air [and] Public Health England estimates [air pollution will lead to] about 2.4 million cases of avoidable illness between now and 2035. We\u2019ve already got more respiratory problems than the rest of Europe and according to the Royal College of Physicians up to 40,000 deaths may be associated with this pollution.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.hsj.co.uk/policy-and-regulation/stevens-nhs-must-take-more-responsibility-for-tackling-climate-change/7025155.article|title=Stevens: NHS must take more responsibility for tackling climate change |last=Mclellan |first=Alastair |date=28 May 2019 |website=Health Service Journal |access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> For these reasons Stevens argues that \"The [[Global warming|climate emergency]] is a health emergency, and we, the NHS, as the single biggest organisation across this country are both part of the solution and part of the problem. We are 40% of public sector emissions, and although we have reduced our carbon footprint by around a fifth over the past decade, we\u2019ve got to make major changes if we\u2019re going to help this country become carbon net neutral.\u201d<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Iacobucci|first=Gareth|date=5 September 2019|title=NHS to step up efforts to tackle \"health emergency\" of climate change|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/366/bmj.l5458|journal=BMJ|language=en|volume=366|pages=l5458|doi=10.1136/bmj.l5458|issn=0959-8138|pmid=31488398}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/air-pollution-child-life-expectancy-birmingham-a8992456.html|title=Air pollution cuts up to seven months off child life expectancy in Birmingham|date=8 July 2019|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe has also argued that the NHS \u2013 as the largest employer in Britain \u2013 is an 'anchor institution' in many local communities, and so needs to \"get more creative in developing staffing and clinical models that will enable us to sustain services and consider second and third order effects in terms of jobs and economic impact and social cohesion\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/policy-and-regulation/stevens-nhs-must-take-more-responsibility-for-tackling-climate-change/7025155.article|title=Stevens: NHS must take more responsibility for tackling climate change|last=Mclellan|first=Alastair|website=Health Service Journal|language=en|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== NHS funding and Brexit ===\nStevens has argued that \"One of the problems with NHS funding over the last 70 years has been its volatility. So, we bounce off the banks between boom and bust and that makes it very hard to plan services.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/health-and-care/nhs/house/house-magazine/96377/simon-stevens-%E2%80%9C-nhs-has-enormous |title=Simon Stevens: Simon Stevens: \"The NHS has an enormous responsibility to be wise stewards of this additional investment\" |date=28 June 2018 |website=PoliticsHome.com |access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref> In November 2017 Stevens gave a high profile speech making the case for a return to NHS funding increases in line with historic norms and independently assessed requirements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fabnhsstuff.net/fab-stuff/simon-stevens-ceo-nhs-england-speech-nhs-providers-birmingham-november-8th-full|title=Simon Stevens, CEO, NHS England \u2013 Speech to NHS Providers, Birmingham, November 8th \u2013 in full |website=Fab NHS Stuff |access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C9478wsR3jw |title=Sky News live coverage of Simon Stevens speech at NHS Providers conference November 2017 |access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref> He did so against the backdrop of a Vote Leave poster which had promised \u00a3350 million a week for the health service and which, he said, the \"public want to see honoured\". His call was widely supported both inside the NHS<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rcseng.ac.uk/news-and-events/media-centre/press-releases/extra-funding-for-nhs/ |title=Royal College of Surgeons|date=8 November 2017 |access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rcgp.org.uk/about-us/news/2017/november/stevens-right-to-call-for-more-nhs-funding-says-rcgp.aspx|title=Royal College of GPs}}</ref> and outside it, ranging from Brexit-supporting Jacob Rees-Mogg{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} to the Remain-supporting general secretary of the TUC.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/nov/09/brexit-promise-350m-a-week-nhs-budget|title=Let's have that Brexit-promised \u00a3350m a week now \u2013 the NHS can't afford to wait |last=O'Grady |first=Frances |date=9 November 2017 |work=The Guardian|access-date=26 January 2019 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018 \u2013 just ahead of the NHS' 70th Anniversary \u2013 the Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] announced extra funding for the NHS worth an average real terms increase of 3.4% a year, reaching \u00a320.5 billion extra in 2023/24.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2018-06-16/nhs-to-get-extra-384-million-per-week-after-brexit-government-says/|title=NHS to get extra \u00c2\u00a3384 million per week after Brexit Government says|website=ITV News|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nStevens led the NHS' 70th anniversary celebrations,<ref>{{Citation|title=NHS success down to \"Brilliance\" of staff says Simon Stevens|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-8URoHHZkZ4|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> including giving the address on 5 July 2018 in the national service of thanksgiving at [[Westminster Abbey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/health/nhs-boss-leads-special-service-at-westminster-abbey-to-celebrate-its-70-years-a3880506.html|title=NHS boss leads special service at Westminster Abbey to celebrate its 70 years|date=5 July 2018|website=Evening Standard|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2018/07/simon-stevens-nhs-70-address-to-westminster-abbey/|title=NHS England \u00bb Simon Stevens' NHS70 address to Westminster Abbey|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.westminster-abbey.org/abbey-news/westminster-abbey-celebrates-70th-anniversary-of-the-nhs/|title=Westminster Abbey celebrates 70th anniversary of the NHS|website=Westminster Abbey|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.westminster-abbey.org/media/8950/nhs-70th-service.pdf|title=Order of Service for Westminster Abbey NHS 70th Anniversary}}</ref>\n\n=== NHS Long Term Plan ===\nOn 7 January 2019 Stevens launched<ref>{{Citation|last=NHS England|title=NHS England Chief Executive Simon Stevens launches the NHS Long Term Plan|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dWFs70mcilU|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref> the [https://www.longtermplan.nhs.uk NHS Long Term Plan], drawn up with patient groups and NHS clinicians. It set out how the NHS will use its extra funding to redesign care and improve outcomes over the decade ahead.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/jan/07/what-is-the-nhs-long-term-plan-and-can-it-achieve-its-aims|title=What is the NHS long-term plan and can it achieve its aims?|last=Boseley|first=Sarah|date=7 January 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The Prime Minister spoke at the launch giving government backing to the plan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/pm-speech-at-nhs-plan-launch-7-january-2019|title=PM speech at NHS plan launch: 7 January 2019|website=GOV.UK|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn drawing up the NHS Long Term Plan, NHS England was also asked by the cross-party House of Commons Health and Social Care Committee, and by the Prime Minister, to make recommendations on possible changes to health legislation. Stevens came forward with proposals to substantially amend the government\u2019s previous [[Health and Social Care Act 2012|2012 legislation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-46827981|title=Are Lansley's NHS reforms being binned?|last=Triggle|first=Nick|date=11 January 2019|access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/feb/28/scrap-laws-driving-privatisation-of-health-service-say-nhs-bosses|title=Scrap laws driving privatisation of health service, say NHS bosses|last=Campbell|first=|date=28 February 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/give-hospitals-freedom-to-work-together-says-nhs-chief-9h7gmwgtj|title=Give hospitals freedom to work together, says NHS chief|last=Smyth|first=Chris|date=27 September 2019|work=The Times|access-date=6 October 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> A wide range of stakeholders called for an NHS Long Term Plan including the Age UK, Macmillan Cancer, the British Red Cross, RCN, Unison, the Medical Royal Colleges, the Kings Fund, NHS Providers, the NHS Confederation, the Local Government Association, Alzheimers Society, British Heart Foundation, Diabetes UK, the Stroke Association and the Patients Association. This letter specifically called for the removal of Section 75 of the 2012 Health and Social Care Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhsconfed.org/-/media/Confederation/Files/Publications/Documents/Support-letter-NHS-legislation-proposals-FINAL.pdf|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The new government of Boris Johnson announced in the Queens Speech of 14 October 2019 that it would back the Long Term Plan, legislate for the \u00a320.5 billion real terms funding increase, and introduce legislation to give effect to the NHS's recommended legal changes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/839370/Queen_s_Speech_Lobby_Pack_2019_.pdf|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nStevens proposed - and NHS England then established - an 'NHS Assembly' to help steer implementation of the NHS Long Term Plan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2019/03/nhs-assembly-announced-to-help-deliver-the-long-term-plan/|title=NHS England \u00bb NHS Assembly announced to help deliver the Long Term Plan|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> It comprises a diverse range of stakeholders including national and local patients' groups, NHS staff and clinical experts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalhealthexecutive.com/Health-Care-News/wide-array-of-nhs-figures-named-as-the-new-nhs-assembly-announced|title=Wide array of NHS figures named as the new NHS Assembly announced|website=www.nationalhealthexecutive.com|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Research and innovation ===\nStevens led action to stop NHS funding of homeopathy, on the grounds that \"There is no robust evidence to support homeopathy, which is at best a placebo and a misuse of scarce NHS funds.\" NHS England was then sued by the British Homeopathic Association who argued that Stevens\u2019 criticisms, including on the BBC Radio Today programme, prejudged its public consultation. The High Court dismissed the BHA challenge, and backed NHS England.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/2018/06/05/high-court-backs-nhs-decision-stop-funding-homeopathy/|title=High Court backs NHS decision to stop funding homeopathy|last=Donnelly|first=Laura|date=5 June 2018|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=26 January 2019|last2=Association|first2=Press|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=THE HONOURABLE MR JUSTICE SUPPERSTONE|title=British Homeopathic Association, R (On the Application Of) v National Health Service Commissioning Board [2018] EWHC 1359 (Admin)|date=5 June 2018|url=http://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2018/1359.html|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nhs-demands-legal-costs-from-failed-homeopathy-challenge-sm80w8kjp|title=NHS demands legal costs from failed homeopathy challenge|last=Smyth|first=Chris|date=31 July 2018|work=The Times|access-date=26 January 2019|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nSpeaking at the [[World Economic Forum]] he launched the first wave of NHS Innovation Test Beds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalhealth.net/2016/01/stevens-launches-innovation-test-beds/|title=Stevens launches innovation 'test beds'|date=22 January 2016|website=Digital Health|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://medicinegov.org/nhs-open-to-global-innovation-healthcare-leaders-launch-search-for-best-new-ideas-from-around-the-world/|title=NHS open to global innovation: healthcare leaders launch search for best new ideas from around the world {{!}}|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> He supports digital hubs<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalhealth.net/2017/09/nhs-england-to-establish-new-digital-innovation-hubs/|title=NHS England to establish new regional Digital Innovation Hubs|date=12 September 2017|website=Digital Health|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> and introduced a new NHS innovation payment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2016/06/treatment-innovations/|title=NHS England \u00bb NHS Chief launches new fast track funding so NHS patients get treatment innovations faster|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> NHS England funds [[Academic Health Science Networks]], and Stevens supported the [[Accelerated Access Review]] arguing:\n\n\"As a nation we need to pursue three goals simultaneously. First, we must actively support new discovery and further development of innovative treatments and care. Second, we have no choice other than to drive value and affordability across the NHS if we're going to create headroom for faster and wider uptake of important new patient treatments. And third, in the run-up to Brexit we need not only to secure - but  enhance - our vibrant and globally successful UK life sciences sector.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/565072/AAR_final.pdf|title=Accelerated Access Review}}</ref>\n\nHe has pushed to deploy AI and Machine Learning in the NHS<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bma.org.uk/news/2017/september/artificial-intelligence-will-be-adopted-says-nhs-england|title=BMA - Artificial intelligence will be adopted, says NHS England|website=www.bma.org.uk|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/hospitals-robots-ai-replace-humans-nhs-simon-stevens-8dhztxtlc|title=Hospitals to get extra cash for using robots and AI to replace humans|last=Aldrick|first=Philip|date=6 June 2019|work=The Times|access-date=6 October 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> and NHS England will be hosting a new \u00a3250 million NHS AI Lab.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/08/uk-government-pledges-303-million-ai-project-for-healthcare.html|title=UK government pledges $303 million for A.I. project to tackle cancer, dementia and heart disease|last=Frangoul|first=Anmar|date=8 August 2019|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nStevens has actively promoted [[genomics]], and cell and gene therapies on the NHS.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/apr/26/nhs-car-t-game-changing-cancer-treatment-immune-therapy|title=NHS preparing to offer 'game-changing' cancer treatment|last=Boseley|first=Sarah|date=26 April 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 January 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/new-cancer-weapon-to-be-fast-tracked-into-hospitals-7dggrqdd5|title=New 'tumour-agnostic' cancer drugs to be fast\u2011tracked into hospitals|last=Whipple|first=Tom|date=19 June 2019|work=The Times|access-date=6 October 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/2019/06/fast-track-game-changing-cancer-drugs/|title=NHS England \u00bb NHS prepares to fast-track 'game changing' cancer drugs that target genetic mutations|website=www.england.nhs.uk|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/sep/04/one-off-injection-will-save-children-from-inherited-blindness|title=One-off injection will save children from inherited blindness|last=Boseley|first=Sarah|date=4 September 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 October 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In Autumn 2018 he announced that the NHS had become the first health service in Europe to negotiate approvals for newly licensed breakthrough [[CAR-T]] cancer therapies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/810e6aaa-b048-11e8-8d14-6f049d06439c|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/cancer-nhs-lymphoma-treatment-health-therapy-a8569441.html|title=NHS strikes deal for cutting edge cancer treatment for adults with lymphoma|date=5 October 2018|website=The Independent|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nStevens is critical of [[homeopathy]], which he maintains is \"fundamentally flawed\". Stevens does not want the [[Society of Homeopaths]] to be reaccredited. Stevens stated: \"This is a vital issue at a time when there is a rise of mis-information about vaccines - some of which is apparently promoted by homeopaths - and which poses a significant danger to human health.\" Stevens added: \"Anything that gives homeopathy a veneer of credibility risks chancers being able to con more people into parting with their hard-earned cash in return for bogus treatments which at best do nothing, and at worst can be potentially dangerous,\" he stated.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/oct/28/head-nhs-voices-serious-concerns-about-homeopathy-simon-stevens |title=Head of NHS voices 'serious concerns' about homeopathy |work=The Guardian |date=28 October 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-50207231 |title=Health bosses' 'serious concerns' over homeopathy |work=BBC News |date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Other activities and awards ==\nStevens was a Visiting Professor at the [[London School of Economics]] from 2004 to 2008, and is an Honorary Fellow of [[Balliol College, University of Oxford]].\n\nHe was awarded an Honorary Doctorate by the [[University of Birmingham]] in 2015, and is also an Honorary Fellow of the [[Royal College of General Practitioners]].\n\nSince becoming NHS England CEO he has given lectures and speeches at the universities of Oxford, Cambridge, Durham, Exeter, London, Birmingham, York, Manchester, Southampton, Newcastle, and previously at Harvard, Yale, and NYU.\n\nHe is regularly interviewed on the [[BBC]], [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], [[Sky News]], ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' and ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|The Today Programme]]'', as well as ''[[The Andrew Marr Show]]''. He has also appeared on ''[[Jeremy Vine (TV programme)|Jeremy Vine]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/p026f1yn|title=Jeremy Vine - Simon Stevens: What Makes Us Human? - BBC Sounds|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> ''[[BBC Breakfast]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BBCBreakfast/status/1082198179427295232|title=Today @NHSEngland will publish its 10-year plan, which will add an extra \u00a320bn per year by 2023. Chief Executive Simon Stevens told #BBCBreakfast what the future of this plan looks like. #NHSEngland #healthcare #fundingpic.twitter.com/FG1j6Bs5In|date=7 January 2019|website=@BBCBreakfast|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> ''[[Any Questions?]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06py0lm|title=David Gauke MP, Bronwen Maddox, John McDonnell MP, Simon Stevens|website=BBC Any Questions|accessdate=7 December 2015}}</ref> and ''[[The One Show]]''.\n\nSince 2013 Stevens has served on the board of directors of the [[Commonwealth Fund]] of New York<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.harknessfellows.org.uk/all-harkness-stories/1990s/simon-stevens|title=Simon Stevens|date=25 May 2018|website=Harkness Fellows|access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> and is a member of its Investment Committee.\n\nHe lists his hobbies as family, offshore sailing, books and 'cooking without recipes'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.director.co.uk/leadership-lessons-simon-stevens-nhs/|title=The leadership lessons of NHS England's Simon Stevens \u2013 Director|date=20 August 2019|website=Director Magazine|language=en-GB|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{NHS England}}\n{{British special advisers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stevens, Simon}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Strathclyde]]\n[[Category:People from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:Chief Executives of the National Health Service]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Lambeth]]\n[[Category:British special advisers]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Oxford Union]]\n[[Category:English healthcare chief executives]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n", "name_user": "Kind Tennis Fan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Consistent dates.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simon_Stevens_(healthcare_manager)"}
{"title_page": "The Fireball", "text_new": "{{about|the 1950 U.S. film|other uses|Fireball (disambiguation)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Fireball\n| image = Fireball11.jpg\n| image size =\n| caption =  VHS cover\n| director = [[Tay Garnett]]<br>[[Charles Kerr (director)|Charles Kerr]] (assistant)\n| producer = [[Bert E. Friedlob]]\t\n| screenplay = [[Horace McCoy]]\n| starring =[[Mickey Rooney]]<br>[[Pat O'Brien (actor)|Pat O'Brien]]\n| cinematography = [[Lester White]]\n| music = [[Victor Young]]\n| editing = [[Frank Sullivan (film editing)|Frank Sullivan]]\n| distributor = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released = {{Film date|1950|11|09}}\n| runtime = 84 minutes\n| language = English\n| country = United States\n| budget =\n}}\n'''''The Fireball''''' is a 1950 American [[drama]] film starring [[Mickey Rooney]] and [[Pat O'Brien (actor)|Pat O'Brien]], and directed by [[Tay Garnett]]. The cast also includes [[Beverly Tyler]] and the eighth screen appearance of [[Marilyn Monroe]].\n\nThe film, released by [[20th Century Fox]], had its screenplay written by [[Horace McCoy]] based on a story by McCoy and Garnett.\n\n==Plot==\nJohnny Casar ([[Mickey Rooney]]) runs away from a home for wayward boys, tired of being teased about being short and a poor athlete. He soon finds a pair of roller skates and is befriended by Bruno Crystal ([[Ralph Dumke]]), who allows him to wash dishes at his caf\u00e9, while a priest who runs the home, Father O'Hara ([[Pat O'Brien (actor)|Pat O'Brien]]), secretly keeps an eye on him.\n\nA traveling roller-skating team takes an interest in Johnny after he shows some aptitude. He clashes with Mack Miller ([[Glen Corbett]]), a cocky champion, and falls for Mary Reeves ([[Beverly Tyler]]), another top skater. Johnny ends up featured in grudge matches against Miller, where they take turns one-upping one another.\n\nAs his fame grows, Johnny becomes every bit as arrogant as Miller and more. Life takes a bad turn when he is diagnosed with [[polio]]. A long period of physical therapy follows, until a wheelchair-bound Johnny tries to get his life back on track.\n\n==Cast (in credits order)==\n*[[Mickey Rooney]] as Johnny Casar\n*[[Pat O'Brien (actor)|Pat O'Brien]] as Father O'Hara\n*[[Beverly Tyler]] as Mary Reeves\n*[[James Brown]] as Allen\n*[[Ralph Dumke]] as Bruno Crystal\n*[[Milburn Stone]] as Jeff Davis\n*[[Bert Begley]] as Shilling\n*[[Marilyn Monroe]] as Polly\n*[[Sam Flint]] as Dr. Barton\n*[[Glen Corbett]] as Mack Miller\n*[[John Hedloe]] as Ullman\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0042463}}\n* {{amg title|158944|The Fireball}}\n* {{tcmdb title|74950|The Fireball}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|1087310-fireball|The Fireball}}\n{{Tay Garnett}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fireball, The}}\n[[Category:1950 films]]\n[[Category:1950s drama films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Tay Garnett]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Victor Young]]\n[[Category:Roller skating films]]\n\n{{1950s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about|the 1950 U.S. film|other uses|Fireball (disambiguation)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Fireball\n| image = Fireball11.jpg\n| image size =\n| caption =  VHS cover\n| director = [[Tay Garnett]]<br>[[Charles Kerr (director)|Charles Kerr]] (assistant)\n| producer = [[Bert E. Friedlob]]\t\n| screenplay = [[Horace McCoy]]\n| starring =[[Mickey Rooney]]<br>[[Pat O'Brien (actor)|Pat O'Brien]]\n| cinematography = [[Lester White]]\n| music = [[Victor Young]]\n| editing = [[Frank Sullivan (film editing)|Frank Sullivan]]\n| distributor = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released = {{Film date|1950|11|09}}\n| runtime = 84 minutes\n| language = English\n| country = United States\n| budget =\n}}\n'''''The Fireball''''' is a 1950 American [[drama]] film starring [[Mickey Rooney]] and [[Pat O'Brien (actor)|Pat O'Brien]], and directed by [[Tay Garnett]]. The cast also includes [[Beverly Tyler]] and the eigth screen appearance of [[Marilyn Monroe]].\n\nThe film, released by [[20th Century Fox]], had its screenplay written by [[Horace McCoy]] based on a story by McCoy and Garnett.\n\n==Plot==\nJohnny Casar ([[Mickey Rooney]]) runs away from a home for wayward boys, tired of being teased about being short and a poor athlete. He soon finds a pair of roller skates and is befriended by Bruno Crystal ([[Ralph Dumke]]), who allows him to wash dishes at his caf\u00e9, while a priest who runs the home, Father O'Hara ([[Pat O'Brien (actor)|Pat O'Brien]]), secretly keeps an eye on him.\n\nA traveling roller-skating team takes an interest in Johnny after he shows some aptitude. He clashes with Mack Miller ([[Glen Corbett]]), a cocky champion, and falls for Mary Reeves ([[Beverly Tyler]]), another top skater. Johnny ends up featured in grudge matches against Miller, where they take turns one-upping one another.\n\nAs his fame grows, Johnny becomes every bit as arrogant as Miller and more. Life takes a bad turn when he is diagnosed with [[polio]]. A long period of physical therapy follows, until a wheelchair-bound Johnny tries to get his life back on track.\n\n==Cast (in credits order)==\n*[[Mickey Rooney]] as Johnny Casar\n*[[Pat O'Brien (actor)|Pat O'Brien]] as Father O'Hara\n*[[Beverly Tyler]] as Mary Reeves\n*[[James Brown]] as Allen\n*[[Ralph Dumke]] as Bruno Crystal\n*[[Milburn Stone]] as Jeff Davis\n*[[Bert Begley]] as Shilling\n*[[Marilyn Monroe]] as Polly\n*[[Sam Flint]] as Dr. Barton\n*[[Glen Corbett]] as Mack Miller\n*[[John Hedloe]] as Ullman\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0042463}}\n* {{amg title|158944|The Fireball}}\n* {{tcmdb title|74950|The Fireball}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|1087310-fireball|The Fireball}}\n{{Tay Garnett}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fireball, The}}\n[[Category:1950 films]]\n[[Category:1950s drama films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Tay Garnett]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Victor Young]]\n[[Category:Roller skating films]]\n\n{{1950s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "EdmundT", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fireball"}
{"title_page": "Reflections (The Supremes song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Reflections\n| cover      = Reflections Supremes.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Supremes|Diana Ross & the Supremes]]\n| album      = [[Reflections (The Supremes album)|Reflections]]\n| B-side     = [[Going Down for the Third Time]]\n| released   = July 24, 1967 <small>([[United States|U.S.]])</small>\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|Vinyl record]] <small>(7\" 45 RPM)</small>\n| recorded   = March 2 and May 9, 1967\n| studio     = [[Hitsville U.S.A.]] (Studio A)\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Psychedelic pop]], [[psychedelic soul]]\n| length     = 2:50 (original release)<br>3:18 (remastered)\n| label      = [[Motown]]<br><small>M 1111</small>\n| writer     = [[Holland\u2013Dozier\u2013Holland]]\n| producer   = [[Brian Holland]] <br /> [[Lamont Dozier]]\n| prev_title = [[The Happening (song)|The Happening]]\n| prev_year  = 1967\n| next_title = [[In and Out of Love (The Supremes song)|In and Out of Love]]\n| next_year  = 1967\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Reflections - The Supremes.ogg\n | description = \"Reflections\"\n}}{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = single\n | cover   = Reflections of the Supremes.png\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption =\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Reflections'''\" is a 1967 song recorded by [[The Supremes]] for the [[Motown]] label. It was the first Supremes record released under the new billing, ''Diana Ross & the Supremes'', and is among their last hit singles to be written and produced by Motown's main production team [[Holland\u2013Dozier\u2013Holland]] (H\u2013D\u2013H).\n\nIt peaked at number 2 on the [[United States]] [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] pop singles chart and number 5 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] in September 1967.<ref>{{cite journal |year=1967 |title=''Billboard'' Hot 100 |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume=79 |issue=36 |page=22 |publisher=[[Nielsen Company]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fSgEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA1&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=8 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThis single, released at the height of the [[Summer of Love]] of [[1967 in music|1967]] and the [[Vietnam War]], was the first Supremes' release to delve into [[psychedelic pop]]; H\u2013D\u2013H's production of the song, influenced by the [[psychedelic rock]] sounds of [[Rock bands|band]]s such as [[The Beatles]] and [[The Beach Boys]], represented a shift in Motown's pop sound during the latter half of the 1960s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lundy|first=Zeth|authorlink=|title=Reflections: Motown in 1967|publisher=PopMatters|date=17 August 2007|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/feature/reflections-motown-in-1967|accessdate=20 January 2010}}</ref> The [[psychedelic era|psychedelic]] influence is apparent in the song's arrangement. Although it is sometimes cited as one of the first mainstream pop recordings to feature a [[Moog synthesizer]], the unusual sounds on the track were generated on a [[test oscillator]] and treated with effects. [[Motown]], the Supremes' record label, purchased a Moog III synthesizer, but not until December 1967.<ref name=\"Brend pp 164-65\">{{cite book|last=Brend|first=Mark|title=The Sound of Tomorrow: How Electronic Music Was Smuggled into the Mainstream|publisher=Bloomsbury Academic|location=London|year=2012|isbn=978-0-8264-2452-5|ref=harv|pp=164\u201365}}</ref>\n\n==Release and reception==\n\"Reflections\" peaked during the late [[summer]] and early [[autumn|fall]] of 1967. Making the highest debut on [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] on the week of August 6, the song reached number 2 on the week ending September 9, 1967. One place short of being the group's 11th American number 1 single, \"Reflections\" stalled at the penultimate position for two weeks behind [[Bobbie Gentry]]'s \"[[Ode to Billie Joe]]\", which Diana Ross re-recorded as a solo for the ''Reflections'' album.<ref>{{cite book|last= Bronson | first = Fred | authorlink = Fred Bronson |title = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] Book of Number 1 Hits | publisher = Billboard Books | year = 2003 | location = 229 | page = 980 | isbn = 978-0-8230-7677-2}}</ref> The single peaked at number 5 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Feldman | first = Christopher | title = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] Book of Number 2 Singles | publisher = Billboard Books | year = 2000 | location = 94 | page = [https://archive.org/details/billboardbookofn00chri/page/288 288] | isbn = 0-8230-7695-4 }}</ref>\n\nThe first nationally televised performance to feature Ballard's replacement [[Cindy Birdsong]] as a member of The Supremes on [[television in the United States|American television]], now billed as \"Diana Ross & the Supremes,\" was on an episode of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] [[variety show|variety program]] ''[[The Hollywood Palace]]''. The episode was hosted by entertainer [[Sammy Davis Jr.]] and first broadcast on September 26, 1967.<ref>{{Cite episode|title= Sammy Davis Jr./Diana Ross & the Supremes|url= http://www.tv.com/host-sammy-davis-jr.---diana-ross-and-supremes/episode/157572/summary.html|series= [[The Hollywood Palace]]|credits= Host: [[Sammy Davis, Jr.]]|network= [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]|station= [[KABC-TV|KABC]]|location= [[Hollywood, Los Angeles, California|Hollywood]]|airdate= 26 September 1967|season= 5|number= 4}}</ref>\n\nA later remastered reissue of the song, running 3:11, although containing the looped section that closes the hit 2:50 single version in the fade-out, features a cold closing as originally recorded.\n\n==Track listing==\n*'''7-inch single (July 24, 1967)''' (North America/United Kingdom)\n#\"Reflections\" \u2013 2:50\n#\"Going Down for the Third Time\" \u2013 2:30\n\n==Personnel==\n*Lead vocals by [[Diana Ross]]\n*Background vocals by [[Florence Ballard]] and [[Mary Wilson (singer)|Mary Wilson]]\n*Instrumentation by [[The Funk Brothers]]\n**[[Earl Van Dyke]] &ndash; [[Wurlitzer electric piano]], [[Hammond organ]], [[test oscillator]]<ref name=\"Brend pp 164-65\" />\n**[[James Jamerson]] &ndash; bass guitar\n**[[Richard \"Pistol\" Allen]] &ndash; drums\n**[[Joe Messina]] &ndash; guitar\n**[[Jack Ashford]] &ndash; percussion\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1967)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|26\n|-\n|Canada ''RPM'' R&B<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.10096d&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.10096d.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.10096d|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1967-09-23 |accessdate=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.10095&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.10095.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.10095|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1967-09-16 |accessdate=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2265 3 *\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|16|song=Reflections|accessdate=June 22, 2017}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Dutch Singles Chart|Netherlands]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[UK Singles Chart]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Billboard Hot 100|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|U.S. ''Billboard'' R&B Singles]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|[[Cashbox (magazine)|U.S. ''Cash Box'']] Top 100\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|}\n\n * - Chart data incomplete\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1967)\n! Rank\n|-\n|Canada<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.100151&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=dtlhqtcdftn9t40n27r4hds2h0 |title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |accessdate=2016-10-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812082630/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.100151&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=dtlhqtcdftn9t40n27r4hds2h0 |archivedate=2016-08-12 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|42\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1967.htm |title=Top 100 Hits of 1967/Top 100 Songs of 1967 |website=MusicOutfitters.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-01}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|41\n|-\n|U.S. ''Cash Box''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/60s_files/1967YESP.html| title=The CASH BOX Year-End Charts: 1967| accessdate=2016-05-08| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304111124/http://50.6.195.142/archives/60s_files/1967YESP.html| archivedate=2016-03-04}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|21\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|the-supremes|reflections}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{The Supremes}}\n{{Holland\u2013Dozier\u2013Holland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reflections (The Supremes Song)}}\n[[Category:1967 singles]]\n[[Category:The Supremes songs]]\n[[Category:Leo Sayer songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Holland\u2013Dozier\u2013Holland]]\n[[Category:GA-Class The Supremes articles]]\n[[Category:Motown singles]]\n[[Category:Psychedelic soul songs]]\n[[Category:1967 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Brian Holland]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Lamont Dozier]]\n[[Category:Television theme songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Reflections\n| cover      = Reflections Supremes.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Supremes|Diana Ross & the Supremes]]\n| album      = [[Reflections (The Supremes album)|Reflections]]\n| B-side     = [[Going Down for the Third Time]]\n| released   = July 24, 1967 <small>([[United States|U.S.]])</small>\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|Vinyl record]] <small>(7\" 45 RPM)</small>\n| recorded   = March 2 and May 9, 1967\n| studio     = [[Hitsville U.S.A.]] (Studio A)\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Psychedelic pop]], [[psychedelic soul]]\n| length     = 2:50 (original release)<br>3:18 (remastered)\n| label      = [[Motown]]<br><small>M 1111</small>\n| writer     = [[Holland\u2013Dozier\u2013Holland]]\n| producer   = [[Brian Holland]] <br /> [[Lamont Dozier]]\n| prev_title = [[The Happening (song)|The Happening]]\n| prev_year  = 1967\n| next_title = [[In and Out of Love (The Supremes song)|In and Out of Love]]\n| next_year  = 1967\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Reflections - The Supremes.ogg\n | description = \"Reflections\"\n}}{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = single\n | cover   = Reflections of the Supremes.png\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption =\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Reflections'''\" is a 1967 song recorded by [[The Supremes]] for the [[Motown]] label. It was the first Supremes record released under the new billing, ''Diana Ross & the Supremes'', and is among their last hit singles to be written and produced by Motown's main production team [[Holland\u2013Dozier\u2013Holland]] (H\u2013D\u2013H).\n\nIt peaked at number 2 on the [[United States]] [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] pop singles chart and number 5 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] in September 1967.<ref>{{cite journal |year=1967 |title=''Billboard'' Hot 100 |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume=79 |issue=36 |page=22 |publisher=[[Nielsen Company]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fSgEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA1&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=8 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThis single, released at the height of the [[Summer of Love]] of [[1967 in music|1967]] and the [[Vietnam War]], was the first Supremes' release to delve into [[psychedelic pop]]; H\u2013D\u2013H's production of the song, influenced by the [[psychedelic rock]] sounds of [[Rock bands|band]]s such as [[The Beatles]] and [[The Beach Boys]], represented a shift in Motown's pop sound during the latter half of the 1960s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lundy|first=Zeth|authorlink=|title=Reflections: Motown in 1967|publisher=PopMatters|date=17 August 2007|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/feature/reflections-motown-in-1967|accessdate=20 January 2010}}</ref> The [[psychedelic era|psychedelic]] influence is apparent in the song's arrangement. Although it is sometimes cited as one of the first mainstream pop recordings to feature a [[Moog synthesizer]], the unusual sounds on the track were generated on a [[test oscillator]] and treated with effects. [[Motown]], the Supremes' record label, purchased a Moog III synthesizer, but not until December 1967.<ref name=\"Brend pp 164-65\">{{cite book|last=Brend|first=Mark|title=The Sound of Tomorrow: How Electronic Music Was Smuggled into the Mainstream|publisher=Bloomsbury Academic|location=London|year=2012|isbn=978-0-8264-2452-5|ref=harv|pp=164\u201365}}</ref>\n\n==Release and reception==\n\"Reflections\" peaked during the late [[summer]] and early [[autumn|fall]] of 1967. Making the highest debut on [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] on the week of August 6, the song reached number 2 on the week ending September 9, 1967. One place short of being the group's 11th American number 1 single, \"Reflections\" stalled at the penultimate position for two weeks behind [[Bobbie Gentry]]'s \"[[Ode to Billie Joe]]\", which Diana Ross re-recorded as a solo for the ''Reflections'' album.<ref>{{cite book|last= Bronson | first = Fred | authorlink = Fred Bronson |title = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] Book of Number 1 Hits | publisher = Billboard Books | year = 2003 | location = 229 | page = 980 | isbn = 978-0-8230-7677-2}}</ref> The single peaked at number 5 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Feldman | first = Christopher | title = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] Book of Number 2 Singles | publisher = Billboard Books | year = 2000 | location = 94 | page = [https://archive.org/details/billboardbookofn00chri/page/288 288] | isbn = 0-8230-7695-4 }}</ref>\n\nThe first nationally televised performance to feature Ballard's replacement [[Cindy Birdsong]] as a member of The Supremes on [[television in the United States|American television]], now billed as \"Diana Ross & the Supremes,\" was on an episode of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] [[variety show|variety program]] ''[[The Hollywood Palace]]''. The episode was hosted by entertainer [[Sammy Davis Jr.]] and first broadcast on September 26, 1967.<ref>{{Cite episode|title= Sammy Davis Jr./Diana Ross & the Supremes|url= http://www.tv.com/host-sammy-davis-jr.---diana-ross-and-supremes/episode/157572/summary.html|series= [[The Hollywood Palace]]|credits= Host: [[Sammy Davis, Jr.]]|network= [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]|station= [[KABC-TV|KABC]]|location= [[Hollywood, Los Angeles, California|Hollywood]]|airdate= 26 September 1967|season= 5|number= 4}}</ref>\n\nA later remastered reissue of the song, running 3:11, although containing the looped section that closes the hit 2:50 single version in the fade-out, features a cold closing as originally recorded.\n\n==Track listing==\n*'''7-inch single (July 24, 1967)''' (North America/United Kingdom)\n#\"Reflections\" \u2013 2:50\n#\"Going Down for the Third Time\" \u2013 2:30\n\n==Personnel==\n*Lead vocals by [[Diana Ross]]\n*Background vocals by [[Florence Ballard]] and [[Mary Wilson (singer)|Mary Wilson]]\n*Instrumentation by [[The Funk Brothers]]\n**[[Earl Van Dyke]] &ndash; [[Wurlitzer electric piano]], [[Hammond organ]], [[test oscillator]]<ref name=\"Brend pp 164-65\" />\n**[[James Jamerson]] &ndash; bass guitar\n**[[Richard \"Pistol\" Allen]] &ndash; drums\n**[[Joe Messina]] &ndash; guitar\n**[[Jack Ashford]] &ndash; percussion\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1967)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|26\n|-\n|Canada ''RPM'' R&B<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.10096d&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.10096d.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.10096d|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1967-09-23 |accessdate=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.10095&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.10095.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.10095|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1967-09-16 |accessdate=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2265 3 *\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|16|song=Reflections|accessdate=June 22, 2017}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Dutch Singles Chart|Netherlands]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[UK Singles Chart]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Billboard Hot 100|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|U.S. ''Billboard'' R&B Singles]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|[[Cashbox (magazine)|