y:Song recordings produced by Lamont Dozier]]\n[[Category:Television theme songs]]\n", "name_user": "JGabbard", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWeekly charts:wf", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reflections_(The_Supremes_song)"}
{"title_page": "Business 2.0", "text_new": "{{Cleanup|external links|date=April 2010}}\n{{Infobox magazine\n| title           = Business 2.0\n| logo            = \n| logo_size       = <!-- default is 180px -->\n| image_file      = <!-- cover.jpg (omit the \"file:\" prefix) -->\n| image_size      = <!-- default is 180px -->\n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = \n| editor          = <!-- up to |editor5= -->\n| editor_title    = <!-- up to |editor_title5= -->\n| previous_editor = \n| staff_writer    = \n| photographer    = \n| category        = \n| frequency       = Monthly\n| format          = \n| circulation     = \n| publisher       = [[Time Inc.]]\n| paid_circulation   = \n| unpaid_circulation = \n| circulation_year   = \n| total_circulation  = \n| founder         = [[Chris Anderson (entrepreneur)|Chris Anderson]]<br>[[James Daly (journalist)|James Daly]]<br>Mark Gross\n| founded         = \n| firstdate       = {{Start date and age|1998|7}}\n| finaldate       = {{End date|2007|10}}\n| finalnumber     = \n| company         = \n| country         = \n| based           = \n| language        = \n| website         = {{URL|money.cnn.com/magazines/business2/business2_archive/}}\n| issn            = \n| oclc            = \n}}\n'''''Business 2.0''''' was a monthly magazine publication founded by magazine entrepreneur [[Chris Anderson (TED)|Chris Anderson]], [[School Loop|Mark Gross]], and journalist [[James Daly (journalist)|James Daly]] in order to chronicle the rise of the \"[[New Economy]]\". First published in July 1998, the magazine was sold to Time Inc., then the publishing division of [[Time Warner]], in July 2001. The magazine failed to make sufficient profit and was shut down; the final issue being published in October 2007. It was based in [[San Francisco, California]].<ref>{{cite news|title=PR Interview: How to Get Into Business 2.0 Magazine|url=https://www.marketingsherpa.com/article/interview/how-to-get-into-business|accessdate=5 December 2015|work=Marketingsherpa|date=9 March 2007}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n''Business 2.0'' enjoyed extraordinary early growth in readers and advertising, selling more than 2000 advertising pages in just its second full year of publishing, believed to be a record for an American monthly newsstand magazine.\n\nThe publication's early competitors included ''[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]'', the ''[[Industry Standard]]'' and ''[[Red Herring (magazine)|Red Herring]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.medialifemagazine.com:8080/news2001/feb01/feb19/2_tues/news1tuesday.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-11-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208080600/http://www.medialifemagazine.com:8080/news2001/feb01/feb19/2_tues/news1tuesday.html |archivedate=2015-12-08 }}</ref>\n\nThe magazine was sold by original publisher [[Future US|Imagine Media]] to [[Time Inc.]], the publishing division of [[Time Warner]], in July 2001. Betting on a tech rebound, Time combined ''Business 2.0'' with its own fledgling business magazine, ''[[eCompany Now]]''. Having originally found success with wonky examinations of the interaction between [[technology]] and business, later on in its run, under the ownership of Time Inc., the magazine broadened its focus, running cover stories on topics ranging from real estate<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/magazines/business2/business2_archive/2006/11/01/toc.html CNN Money] November 1, 2006.</ref> to employment trends<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/magazines/business2/business2_archive/2006/05/01/toc.html CNN Money] May 1, 2006</ref> and outer space.<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/magazines/business2/business2_archive/2006/03/01/toc.html CNN Money] March 1, 2006</ref>\n\nDespite an upturn in the fortunes of startups and technology companies, ''Business 2.0'' was unable to turn a profit. [[Josh Quittner]], the editor since 2002, who had previously helmed ''Netly News'' and ''ON Magazine'', led a team that published out of the ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' Group of Time Inc.\n\nIn November 2006, in an effort to connect with the large numbers of readers who had come to rely on web blogs for news, ''Business 2.0'' launched a series of staff written blogs.\n\nIn July 2007 ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that the September issue could be the magazine's last. In response to these reports a number of readers organized a [[Facebook]] group called ''I read Business 2.0. And I want to keep reading!'' to speak out against [[Time Inc.]]'s possible decision to close the publication. Nevertheless, on September 5, 2007, ''The New York Times'' reported that Time Inc. had confirmed it would shut down ''Business 2.0'' with its October 2007 issue<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/05/business/media/05mag.html?_r=1&oref=slogin New York Times: \"Time Inc. to ''Close Business 2.0'',\" Sept. 5, 2007]</ref> \"as the magazine\u2019s ad pages precipitously dropped this year\".<ref>[http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/09/04/business-20-rip/ New York Times] September 4, 2007.</ref> A number of the reporters and editors have been transferred to work on ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]''.\n\n==Notable features and articles==\nIn its first issue (coverline \"New Rules\") it included a specially printed insert devoted to \"The 10 Driving Principles of the New Economy,\" adding an eleventh (partnerships) to the list in 2000.\n\nThe original principles, released in the magazine's inaugural issue in July 1998, are:\n* Matter. (It matters less.)\n* Space. (Distance has vanished.)\n* Time. (It is collapsing.)\n* People. (They're the crown jewels.)\n* Growth. (It's accelerated by the network.)\n* Value. (It rises exponentially with market share.)\n* Efficiency. (The middleman lives on in \"infomediaries\".)\n* Markets. (Buyers are gaining dramatic new power, sellers new opportunities.)\n* Transactions. (It's a one-on-one game.)\n* Impulse. (Every product is available everywhere.)\n\nAt the beginning of every year, ''Business 2.0'' printed its snarky list of the \"101 Dumbest Moments in Business\" [http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2007/biz2/0701/gallery.101dumbest_2007/index.html] that had occurred during the previous year. ''Fortune'' has inherited this tradition.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Web 2.0]]\n*[[Business Intelligence 2.0]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://money.cnn.com/magazines/business2/business2_archive/ Searchable archives at CNN Money]\n* [https://www.forbes.com/media/2007/07/17/magazines-silicon-valley-biz-media-cx_bc_0717business.html Bye Bye Business 2.0 - Forbes.com]\n* [http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/09/04/business-20-rip/ Business 2.0 RIP - The New York Times]\n* [https://techcrunch.com/2007/09/04/dodos-to-business-20-welcome-to-the-club/ Dodos to Business 2.0: Welcome To The Club - TechCrunch]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071018073222/http://www.blogmagazine.com/blog_magazine/2007/09/business-20-bit.html Business 2.0 Bites the Dust - Blog Magazine]\n* [https://techcrunch.com/2007/09/19/business-20-the-final-cover/ Business 2.0: The Final Cover - TechCrunch]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071018053641/http://gawker.com/news/business-2.0/business-20-stricken-with-bad-case-of-blog-212211.php Business 2.0 Stricken With A Bad Case of Blog - Gawker]\n\n{{AT&T}}\n\n[[Category:American business magazines]]\n[[Category:American monthly magazines]]\n[[Category:Defunct magazines of the United States]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 2007]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in San Francisco]]\n", "text_old": "{{Cleanup|external links|date=April 2010}}\n{{Infobox magazine\n| title           = Business 2.0\n| logo            = \n| logo_size       = <!-- default is 180px -->\n| image_file      = <!-- cover.jpg (omit the \"file:\" prefix) -->\n| image_size      = <!-- default is 180px -->\n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = \n| editor          = <!-- up to |editor5= -->\n| editor_title    = <!-- up to |editor_title5= -->\n| previous_editor = \n| staff_writer    = \n| photographer    = \n| category        = \n| frequency       = Monthly\n| format          = \n| circulation     = \n| publisher       = [[Time Inc.]]\n| paid_circulation   = \n| unpaid_circulation = \n| circulation_year   = \n| total_circulation  = \n| founder         = [[Chris Anderson (entrepreneur)|Chris Anderson]]<br>[[James Daly (journalist)|James Daly]]<br>Mark Gross\n| founded         = \n| firstdate       = {{Start date and age|1998|7}}\n| finaldate       = {{End date|2007|10}}\n| finalnumber     = \n| company         = \n| country         = \n| based           = \n| language        = \n| website         = {{URL|money.cnn.com/magazines/business2/business2_archive/}}\n| issn            = \n| oclc            = \n}}\n'''''Business 2.0''''' was a monthly magazine publication founded by magazine entrepreneur [[Chris Anderson (TED)|Chris Anderson]], [[School Loop|Mark Gross]], and journalist [[James Daly (journalist)|James Daly]] in order to chronicle the rise of the \"[[New Economy]]\". First published in July 1998, the magazine was sold to Time Inc., then the publishing division of [[Time Warner]], in July 2001. The magazine failed to make sufficient profit and was shut down; the final issue being published in October 2007. It was based in [[San Francisco, California]].<ref>{{cite news|title=PR Interview: How to Get Into Business 2.0 Magazine|url=https://www.marketingsherpa.com/article/interview/how-to-get-into-business|accessdate=5 December 2015|work=Marketingsherpa|date=9 March 2007}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n''Business 2.0'' enjoyed extraordinary early growth in readers and advertising, selling more than 2000 advertising pages in just its second full year of publishing, believed to be a record for an American monthly newsstand magazine.\n\nThe publication's early competitors included ''[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]'', the ''[[Industry Standard]]'' and ''[[Red Herring (magazine)|Red Herring]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.medialifemagazine.com:8080/news2001/feb01/feb19/2_tues/news1tuesday.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-11-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208080600/http://www.medialifemagazine.com:8080/news2001/feb01/feb19/2_tues/news1tuesday.html |archivedate=2015-12-08 }}</ref>\n\nThe magazine was sold by original publisher [[Future US|Imagine Media]] to [[Time Inc.]], the publishing division of [[Time Warner]], in July 2001. Betting on a tech rebound, Time combined ''Business 2.0'' with its own fledgling business magazine, ''[[eCompany Now]]''. Having originally found success with wonky examinations of the interaction between [[technology]] and business, later on in its run, under the ownership of Time Inc., the magazine broadened its focus, running cover stories on topics ranging from real estate<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/magazines/business2/business2_archive/2006/11/01/toc.html CNN Money] November 1, 2006.</ref> to employment trends<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/magazines/business2/business2_archive/2006/05/01/toc.html CNN Money] May 1, 2006</ref> and outer space.<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/magazines/business2/business2_archive/2006/03/01/toc.html CNN Money] March 1, 2006</ref>\n\nDespite an upturn in the fortunes of startups and technology companies, ''Business 2.0'' was unable to turn a profit. [[Josh Quittner]], the editor since 2002, who had previously helmed ''Netly News'' and ''ON Magazine'', led a team that published out of the ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' Group of Time Inc.\n\nIn November 2006, in an effort to connect with the large numbers of readers who had come to rely on web blogs for news, ''Business 2.0'' launched a series of staff written blogs.\n\nIn July 2007 ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that the September issue could be the magazine's last. In response to these reports a number of readers organized a [[Facebook]] group called ''I read Business 2.0. And I want to keep reading!'' to speak out against [[Time Inc.]]'s possible decision to close the publication. Nevertheless, on September 5, 2007, ''The New York Times'' reported that Time Inc. had confirmed it would shut down ''Business 2.0'' with its October 2007 issue<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/05/business/media/05mag.html?_r=1&oref=slogin New York Times: \"Time Inc. to ''Close Business 2.0'',\" Sept. 5, 2007]</ref> \"as the magazine\u2019s ad pages precipitously dropped this year\".<ref>[http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/09/04/business-20-rip/ New York Times] September 4, 2007.</ref> A number of the reporters and editors have been transferred to work on ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]''.\n\n==Notable features and articles==\nIn its first issue (coverline \"New Rules\") it included a specially printed insert devoted to \"The 10 Driving Principles of the New Economy,\" adding an eleventh (partnerships) to the list in 2000.\n\nThe original principles, released in the magazine's inaugural issue in July 1998, are:\n* Matter. (It matters less.)\n* Space. (Distance has vanished.)\n* Time. (It is collapsing.)\n* People. (They're the crown jewels.)\n* Growth. (It's accelerated by the network.)\n* Value. (It rises exponentially with market share.)\n* Efficiency. (The middleman lives on in \"infomediaries\".)\n* Markets. (Buyers are gaining dramatic new power, sellers new opportunities.)\n* Transactions. (It's a one-on-one game.)\n* Impulse. (Every product is available everywhere.)\n\nAt the beginning of every year, ''Business 2.0'' printed its snarky list of the \"101 Dumbest Moments in Business\" [http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2007/biz2/0701/gallery.101dumbest_2007/index.html] that had occurred during the previous year. ''Fortune'' has inherited this tradition.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Web 2.0]]\n*[[Business Intelligence 2.0]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://money.cnn.com/magazines/business2/business2_archive/ Searchable archives at CNN Money]\n* [https://www.forbes.com/media/2007/07/17/magazines-silicon-valley-biz-media-cx_bc_0717business.html Bye Bye Business 2.0 - Forbes.com]\n* [http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/09/04/business-20-rip/ Business 2.0 RIP - The New York Times]\n* [https://techcrunch.com/2007/09/04/dodos-to-business-20-welcome-to-the-club/ Dodos to Business 2.0: Welcome To The Club - TechCrunch]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071018073222/http://www.blogmagazine.com/blog_magazine/2007/09/business-20-bit.html Business 2.0 Bites the Dust - Blog Magazine]\n* [https://techcrunch.com/2007/09/19/business-20-the-final-cover/ Business 2.0: The Final Cover - TechCrunch]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071018053641/http://gawker.com/news/business-2.0/business-20-stricken-with-bad-case-of-blog-212211.php Business 2.0 Stricken With A Bad Case of Blog - Gawker]\n\n{{AT&T}}\n\n[[Category:American business magazines]]\n[[Category:American monthly magazines]]\n[[Category:Defunct magazines of the United States]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 2007]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in California]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Business_2.0"}
{"title_page": "Battle of Altenheim", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict= Battle of Altenheim\n|partof=[[Franco-Dutch War]]\n| image=\n| image_size =\n|caption=\n|date=1 August 1675\n|place=Altenheim, [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]] {{efn|Not to be confused with the nearby French town of [[Altenheim]]}}\n|casus= 1675 [[Rhineland]] Campaign of the [[Franco-Dutch]] War\n|territory=\n|result= Inconclusive\n|combatant1={{flagcountry|Kingdom of France}}\n|combatant2={{flagcountry|Holy Roman Empire}}\n|commander1={{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Guy_Aldonce_de_Durfort_de_Lorges|de Lorges]] <br/> {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}}  de Vaubrun {{KIA}}\n|commander2={{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Raimondo Montecuccoli]]\n|strength1=10,000 infantry, 9,000 cavalry, 1,000 dragoons <br> 30 guns <ref>{{cite book |last1=De P\u00e9rini |first1=Hard\u00ff |title=Batailles fran\u00e7aises |date=1896 |publisher=Ernest Flammarion, Paris|page=146 |url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k750505/f162.item.r=Altenheim |accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref> \n|strength2=30,000 {{efn|Maximum; these are the figures given by De P\u00e9rini at the beginning of the campaign.}}\n|casualties1=3,000\n|casualties2=4,500 <ref>{{cite book |last1=De P\u00e9rini |first1=Hard\u00ff |title=Batailles fran\u00e7aises |date=1896 |publisher=Ernest Flammarion, Paris|page=161 |url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k750505/f162.item.r=Altenheim |accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref> \n|notes=\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Dutch War}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Altenheim''' took place on 1 August 1675 during the 1672-1678 [[Franco-Dutch War]] near [[Altenheim]], in modern [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], between a French army jointly commanded by the Marquis de Vaubrun and the [[Guy_Aldonce_de_Durfort_de_Lorges|Comte de Lorges]] and an [[Imperial Army (Holy Roman Empire)|Imperial Army]] under [[Raimondo Montecuccoli]]. Having lost their commander [[Henri_de_La_Tour_d'Auvergne,_Viscount_of_Turenne|Marshall Turenne]] on 27 July, the French retreated over the [[Rhine]], using the bridge at Altenheim; the Imperialists tried to prevent them but were unable to do so, despite heavy casualties on both sides. \n\n==Background==\nDuring the 1667-1668 [[War of Devolution]], France captured most of the [[Spanish Netherlands]] but under the [[Treaty_of_Aix-la-Chapelle_(1668)|Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle]], it was forced to relinquish most of these gains by the [[Triple Alliance (1668)|Triple Alliance]] between the [[Dutch Republic]], England and [[Sweden]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lynn |first1=John |title=The Wars of Louis XIV, 1667-1714 (Modern Wars In Perspective) |date=1996 |publisher=Longman |isbn=978-0582056299 |page=[https://archive.org/details/warsoflouisxiv1600lynn/page/109 109] |url=https://archive.org/details/warsoflouisxiv1600lynn/page/109 }}</ref>\n[[File:Henri de la Tour d'Auvergne, Vicomte de Turenne by Circle of Philippe de Champaigne.jpg|150px|left|thumb|[[Henri_de_La_Tour_d'Auvergne,_Viscount_of_Turenne|Marshall Turenne]], considered the best general of his time, killed at [[Battle_of_Salzbach|Salzbach]] on 27 July 1675]] \n[[Louis_XIV_of_France|Louis XIV]] now moved to break up the Alliance before making another attempt on the Spanish Netherlands. In return for large subsidies, Sweden agreed to remain neutral and to attack its regional rival, [[Brandenburg-Prussia]] if it attempted to intervene. In 1670, [[Charles II of England]] signed the [[Secret_Treaty_of_Dover|Treaty of Dover]], agreeing to an alliance with France against the Dutch, and the provision of 6,000 English and Scottish troops for the French army.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lynn |first1=John |title=The Wars of Louis XIV, 1667-1714 (Modern Wars In Perspective) |date=1996 |publisher=Longman |isbn=978-0582056299 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/warsoflouisxiv1600lynn/page/109 109\u2013110] |url=https://archive.org/details/warsoflouisxiv1600lynn/page/109 }}</ref> It also contained a number of secret provisions, not revealed until 1771, one being the payment by Louis to Charles of \u00a3230,000 per year for the services of this Brigade.<ref>J. P. Kenyon, ''The History Men. The Historical Profession in England since the Renaissance. Second Edition'' (Weidenfeld and Nicolson, 1993), pp. 67-68.</ref>\n\nFrance invaded the Dutch Republic in May 1672 and seemed at first to have achieved an overwhelming victory. However, the Dutch position stabilised, while concern at French gains brought support from [[Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg|Frederick William of Brandenburg-Prussia]], [[Leopold I, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Leopold]] and [[Charles II of Spain]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Rhea |title=Spain; A Modern History |url=https://archive.org/details/spainmodernhisto00smit |url-access=registration |date=1965 |publisher=University of Michigan Press |isbn=978-0472071500 |page=[https://archive.org/details/spainmodernhisto00smit/page/200 200]}}</ref> Louis was now forced into another war of attrition around the French frontiers and in August, an Imperial army opened a new front in the [[Rhineland]].<ref name=\"Lynn 1999, p. 117\">Lynn 1999, p. 117.</ref> \n[[File:Schwarzwald - Deutsche Mittelgebirge, Serie A-de.png|thumb|left|250px|The Rhineland area 1674-1675, [[Strasbourg]] upper left; note the narrow corridor between the [[Rhine]] and the [[Black Forest]]]]\nThe French army in Germany was led by [[Henri de la Tour d'Auvergne, Vicomte de Turenne|Turenne]], (1611-1675), considered the greatest general of the period.<ref>{{cite web |title=Turenne 1611-1675 |url=https://www.museeprotestant.org/en/notice/turenne-1611-1675-2/ |website=Mus\u00e9e virtuel du Protestantisme |accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref> Over the next two years, he won a series of victories over superior Imperial forces led by [[Alexander von Bournonville]] and [[Raimondo Montecuccoli]], the one commander contemporaries viewed as equal to Turenne.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Guthrie |first1=William |title=The Later Thirty Years War: From the Battle of Wittstock to the Treaty of Westphalia (Contributions in Military Studies) |date=2003 |publisher=Praeger |isbn=978-0313324086 |page=239}}</ref> France found itself over-extended, a problem that increased in January 1674 when [[Denmark\u2013Norway|Denmark]] joined the Alliance; in February, England left the war by signing the [[Treaty of Westminster (1674)|Treaty of Westminster]] with the Dutch Republic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/europeantreaties02daveuoft |page=238|title=European Treaties bearing on the History of the United States and its Dependencies|year=1917|authorlink=Frances Gardiner Davenport|first=Frances|last=Davenport|accessdate=7 October 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Raimondo-montecuccoli.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Imperial General [[Raimondo Montecuccoli]]; contemporaries viewed him as Turenne's only equal]]\nThe campaign that started in June 1674 and ended with his death in July 1675, has been described as 'possibly Turenne's most brilliant campaign.'<ref>{{cite book |last1=Clodfelter |first1=Micheal |title=Warfare and Armed Conflicts: A Statistical Encyclopedia of Casualty and Other Figures, 1494-2007 |url=https://archive.org/details/warfarearmedconf0000clod/page/46 |url-access=registration |date=2008 |publisher=McFarland & Co |isbn=978-0786433193 |page=46}}</ref> Significantly outnumbered, he fought Bournonville to a standstill at [[Battle_of_Entzheim|Entzheim]] in early October, followed by a surprise winter attack that culminated in another decisive victory at the [[Battle of Turckheim]] in January 1675.<ref>Lynn, 1999, 127.</ref> \n\nMontecuccoli brought up another 25,000 men and combined with the remnants of Bournonville's force, this meant Turenne was outnumbered once more. By late May, the Imperial army was at [[Oberkirch_(Baden)|Oberkirch]], preparing to take the bridge at [[Kehl]] and re-establish contact with Strasburg. The next two months were spent in a series of marches and counter-marches, with Turenne seeking to remain in close contact with the Imperialists. Local geography restricted them to a relatively narrow corridor between the left bank of the [[Rhine]] and the [[Black Forest]], other factors being a dependence on waterways for moving supplies, the need to obtain forage for cavalry and transport, while persistent rain in the first half of June made movement almost impossible.<ref name=\"De P\u00e9rini, p. 151-152\">De P\u00e9rini, p. 151-152.</ref>  \n\nA number of skirmishes and encounters took place in July as each commander attempted to outwit the other, the Marquis de Vaubrun being wounded in one of these on 24 July. On 25 July, Montecuccoli stopped between [[Gro\u00dfweier]] and [[Sasbach_(Ortenau)|Sasbach]], as he waited for his subordinate [[Aeneas de Caprara]] to rejoin him from [[Offenburg]]. On the morning of 27th, Turenne arrived at [[Battle_of_Salzbach|Salzbach]], looking for an opportunity to attack; he was checking the position of his artillery in the afternoon, when he was killed by a cannonball.<ref>Lynn, 1999, 141.</ref>\n\n==The Battle==\n[[Image:Blondel - Guy Aldonce de Durfort de Lorges (1630-1702) - MV 1042.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Guy Aldonce de Durfort de Lorges]]; Turenne's nephew, who disputed command with Vaubrun]]\nThe news of Turenne's death was initially concealed from the troops, but it soon became common knowledge. Turenne had no direct subordinate but two 'Lieutenant-Generals,' his nephew, the Comte [[Guy_Aldonce_de_Durfort_de_Lorges|de Lorges]] and the Marquis de Vaubrun, who rotated the position on a daily basis. According to another officer, the [[Antoine_de_Pas_de_Feuqui\u00e8res|Marquis de Feuqui\u00e8res]], de Lorges and de Vaubrun now spent the next three days arguing who should assume command, at one point drawing swords on each other in the middle of the camp.<ref>{{cite book |last1=De P\u00e9rini |first1=Hard\u00ff |title=Batailles fran\u00e7aises |date=1896 |publisher=Ernest Flammarion, Paris|page=161 |url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k750505/f162.item.r=Altenheim |accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe French baggage train was stationed in the nearby village of [[Willst\u00e4tt]]; hoping to capture it and re-establish direct communication with Strasburg, a force of Imperial dragoons and cavalry unsuccessfully attacked on 29 July. De Lorge and de Vaubrun finally compromised by agreeing to rotate command daily and on 31 July, the French army moved towards the bridge over the Rhine at [[Altenheim]], a small town now part of the municipality of [[Neuried]] in [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]]. As they did so, Montecuccoli followed up, once more threatening to take Willst\u00e4tt and the French supplies.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Almon |first1=John |title=A new military dictionary: or, the field of war. Containing a particular account of the most remarkable battles, sieges, bombardments, and relate to Great Britain and her dependencies |date=1760 |publisher=Gale ECCO |isbn=978-1385700778 |page=4 |edition=2018 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=8ulhAAAAcAAJ&pg=PT39&lpg=PT39&dq=battle+of+altenheim#v=onepage&q=battle%20of%20altenheim&f=false}}</ref>   \n\nA second dispute broke out between De Lorges and de Vaubrun as to whether to continue towards the bridge or save the stores. They decided to first destroy the stores, then cross, but the delay left the army divided when night came on 31st, with Vaubrun's vanguard on the French side of the Rhine and the rest under de Lorges yet to cross.<ref name=\"Almon 1760, p. 4\">Almon 1760, p. 4.</ref> \nTo reach the Rhine, de Lorges' troops had to first cross a smaller tributary called the [[Schutter_(Kinzig)|Schutter]]. As they began doing so on 1 August, Montecuccoli attacked, while simultaneously cutting off their retreat by taking the bridge at Altenheim. Vaubrun had been wounded in the leg on 24 July and was tied onto his horse; he counter-attacked with 16 squadrons of cavalry and eight battalions of infantry and was killed in the action, but the Imperialists were driven out of Altenheim. The French rearguard was composed of the ''Brigade de Champagne,'' which included the British regiments; it repulsed a series of assaults and fighting ended around evening, with both sides withdrawing.<ref name=\"Almon 1760, p. 4\">Almon 1760, p. 4.</ref> \n[[File:Louis, Grand Cond\u00e9.PNG|thumb|right|150px|[[Louis,_Grand_Cond\u00e9|le Grand Cond\u00e9]], who replaced Turenne a few days after Altenheim]]\nDe Feuqui\u00e8res, part of the ''Brigade de Champagne,'' described this action in his 'Memoirs' as one of the 'most glorious in the history of France.' The brigade lost 10 captains and 25 lieutenants killed, French casualties being around 3,000 to the Imperialists 4,500.<ref name=\"De P\u00e9rini, p. 161\">De P\u00e9rini, p. 161.</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe French withdrew to [[S\u00e9lestat]] and the [[Louis,_Grand_Cond\u00e9|Prince of Cond\u00e9]] assumed command; he was a capable general, responsible for victory at [[Battle_of_Seneffe|Seneffe]] in 1674 but in poor health and this would be his last campaign. On 11 August, a French force of 15,000 sent to relieve [[Trier]] was defeated at [[Battle_of_Konzer_Br\u00fccke|Konzer Br\u00fccke]] and Trier surrendered in September. Unwilling to risk losing the only remaining French army in the Rhineland and estimating Imperial strength at over 30,000, Cond\u00e9 took up position at the fortified town of [[Ch\u00e2tenois, Bas-Rhin|Ch\u00e2tenois]]. Montecuccoli attempted to lure him out, but with French cavalry raiding his supply lines and winter coming on, he abandoned the attempt, In the first week of November, his army recrossed the Rhine and went into winter quarters.<ref name=\"De P\u00e9rini, p. 168-171\">De P\u00e9rini, p. 168-171.</ref>        \n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* Almon, John; ''A new military dictionary: or, the field of war. Containing a particular account of the most remarkable battles, sieges, bombardments, and relate to Great Britain and her dependencies;'' (First published 1760, Gale ECCO, 2018 ed);\n* Clodfelter, Micheal; ''Warfare and Armed Conflicts: A Statistical Encyclopedia of Casualty and Other Figures, 1494-2007;'' (McFarland & Co, 2008);\n* Davenport, Frances; ''European Treaties bearing on the History of the United States and its Dependencies;'' (Published 1917, Andesite Press, 2017 ed);\n* De P\u00e9rini, Hard\u00ff; ''Batailles fran\u00e7aises, 1672-1700;'' (Ernest Flammarion, Paris, 1896);\n* Guthrie, William; ''The Later Thirty Years War: From the Battle of Wittstock to the Treaty of Westphalia (Contributions in Military Studies);'' (Praeger, 2003);\n* Kenyon, J.P.; ''The History Men. The Historical Profession in England since the Renaissance;'' (Weidenfeld and Nicolson, 1993);\n* Lynn, John; ''The Wars of Louis XIV, 1667-1714 (Modern Wars In Perspective);'' (Longman, 1996); \n* Smith, Rhea; (1965). ''Spain; A Modern History;'' (University of Michigan Press, 1965);\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite web |title=Turenne 1611-1675 |url=https://www.museeprotestant.org/en/notice/turenne-1611-1675-2/ |website=Mus\u00e9e virtuel du Protestantisme |accessdate=19 October 2018}};\n\n\n{{coord|48.5353|N|7.6381|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Altenheim, Battle of}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1675]]\n[[Category:1675 in Europe]]\n[[Category:Battles involving France]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Holy Roman Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict= Battle of Altenheim\n|partof=[[Franco-Dutch War]]\n| image=\n| image_size =\n|caption=\n|date=1 August 1675\n|place=Altenheim, [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]] {{efn|Not to be confused with the nearby French town of [[Altenheim]]}}\n|casus= 1675 [[Rhineland]] Campaign of the [[Franco-Dutch]] War\n|territory=\n|result= Inconclusive\n|combatant1={{flagcountry|Kingdom of France}}\n|combatant2={{flagcountry|Holy Roman Empire}}\n|commander1={{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Guy_Aldonce_de_Durfort_de_Lorges|de Lorges]] <br/> {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}}  de Vaubrun {{KIA}}\n|commander2={{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Raimondo Montecuccoli]]\n|strength1=10,000 infantry, 9,000 cavalry, 1,000 dragoons <br> 30 guns <ref>{{cite book |last1=De P\u00e9rini |first1=Hard\u00ff |title=Batailles fran\u00e7aises |date=1896 |publisher=Ernest Flammarion, Paris|page=146 |url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k750505/f162.item.r=Altenheim |accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref> \n|strength2=30,000 {{efn|Maximum; these are the figures given by De P\u00e9rini at the beginning of the campaign.}}\n|casualties1=3,000\n|casualties2=4,500 <ref>{{cite book |last1=De P\u00e9rini |first1=Hard\u00ff |title=Batailles fran\u00e7aises |date=1896 |publisher=Ernest Flammarion, Paris|page=161 |url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k750505/f162.item.r=Altenheim |accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref> \n|notes=\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Dutch War}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Altenheim''' took place on 1 August 1675 during the 1672-1678 [[Franco-Dutch War]] near [[Altenheim]], in modern [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], between a French army jointly commanded by the Marquis de Vaubrun and the [[Guy_Aldonce_de_Durfort_de_Lorges|Comte de Lorges]] and an [[Imperial Army (Holy Roman Empire)|Imperial Army]] under [[Raimondo Montecuccoli]]. Having lost their commander [[Henri_de_La_Tour_d'Auvergne,_Viscount_of_Turenne|Marshall Turenne]] on 27 July, the French retreated over the [[Rhine]], using the bridge at Altenheim; the Imperialists tried to prevent them but were unable to do so, despite heavy casualties on both sides. \n\n==Background==\nDuring the 1667-1668 [[War of Devolution]], France captured most of the [[Spanish Netherlands]] but under the [[Treaty_of_Aix-la-Chapelle_(1668)|Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle]], it was forced to relinquish most of these gains by the [[Triple Alliance (1668)|Triple Alliance]] between the [[Dutch Republic]], England and [[Sweden]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lynn |first1=John |title=The Wars of Louis XIV, 1667-1714 (Modern Wars In Perspective) |date=1996 |publisher=Longman |isbn=978-0582056299 |page=[https://archive.org/details/warsoflouisxiv1600lynn/page/109 109] |url=https://archive.org/details/warsoflouisxiv1600lynn/page/109 }}</ref>\n[[File:Henri de la Tour d'Auvergne, Vicomte de Turenne by Circle of Philippe de Champaigne.jpg|150px|left|thumb|[[Henri_de_La_Tour_d'Auvergne,_Viscount_of_Turenne|Marshall Turenne]], considered the best general of his time, killed at [[Battle_of_Salzbach|Salzbach]] on 27 July 1675]] \n[[Louis_XIV_of_France|Louis XIV]] now moved to break up the Alliance before making another attempt on the Spanish Netherlands. In return for large subsidies, Sweden agreed to remain neutral and to attack its regional rival, [[Brandenburg-Prussia]] if it attempted to intervene. In 1670, [[Charles II of England]] signed the [[Secret_Treaty_of_Dover|Treaty of Dover]], agreeing to an alliance with France against the Dutch, and the provision of 6,000 English and Scottish troops for the French army.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lynn |first1=John |title=The Wars of Louis XIV, 1667-1714 (Modern Wars In Perspective) |date=1996 |publisher=Longman |isbn=978-0582056299 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/warsoflouisxiv1600lynn/page/109 109\u2013110] |url=https://archive.org/details/warsoflouisxiv1600lynn/page/109 }}</ref> It also contained a number of secret provisions, not revealed until 1771, one being the payment by Louis to Charles of \u00a3230,000 per year for the services of this Brigade.<ref>J. P. Kenyon, ''The History Men. The Historical Profession in England since the Renaissance. Second Edition'' (Weidenfeld and Nicolson, 1993), pp. 67-68.</ref>\n\nFrance invaded the Dutch Republic in May 1672 and seemed at first to have achieved an overwhelming victory. However, the Dutch position stabilised, while concern at French gains brought support from [[Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg|Frederick William of Brandenburg-Prussia]], [[Leopold I, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Leopold]] and [[Charles II of Spain]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Rhea |title=Spain; A Modern History |url=https://archive.org/details/spainmodernhisto00smit |url-access=registration |date=1965 |publisher=University of Michigan Press |isbn=978-0472071500 |page=[https://archive.org/details/spainmodernhisto00smit/page/200 200]}}</ref> Louis was now forced into another war of attrition around the French frontiers and in August, an Imperial army opened a new front in the [[Rhineland]].<ref name=\"Lynn 1999, p. 117\">Lynn 1999, p. 117.</ref> \n[[File:Schwarzwald - Deutsche Mittelgebirge, Serie A-de.png|thumb|left|250px|The Rhineland area 1674-1675, [[Strasbourg]] upper left; note the narrow corridor between the [[Rhine]] and the [[Black Forest]]]]\nThe French army in Germany was led by [[Henri de la Tour d'Auvergne, Vicomte de Turenne|Turenne]], (1611-1675), considered the greatest general of the period.<ref>{{cite web |title=Turenne 1611-1675 |url=https://www.museeprotestant.org/en/notice/turenne-1611-1675-2/ |website=Mus\u00e9e virtuel du Protestantisme |accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref> Over the next two years, he won a series of victories over superior Imperial forces led by [[Alexander von Bournonville]] and [[Raimondo Montecuccoli]], the one commander contemporaries viewed as equal to Turenne.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Guthrie |first1=William |title=The Later Thirty Years War: From the Battle of Wittstock to the Treaty of Westphalia (Contributions in Military Studies) |date=2003 |publisher=Praeger |isbn=978-0313324086 |page=239}}</ref> France found itself over-extended, a problem that increased in January 1674 when [[Denmark\u2013Norway|Denmark]] joined the Alliance; in February, England left the war by signing the [[Treaty of Westminster (1674)|Treaty of Westminster]] with the Dutch Republic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/europeantreaties02daveuoft |page=238|title=European Treaties bearing on the History of the United States and its Dependencies|year=1917|authorlink=Frances Gardiner Davenport|first=Frances|last=Davenport|accessdate=7 October 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Raimondo-montecuccoli.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Imperial General [[Raimondo Montecuccoli]]; contemporaries viewed him as Turenne's only equal]]\nThe campaign that started in June 1674 and ended with his death in July 1675, has been described as 'possibly Turenne's most brilliant campaign.'<ref>{{cite book |last1=Clodfelter |first1=Micheal |title=Warfare and Armed Conflicts: A Statistical Encyclopedia of Casualty and Other Figures, 1494-2007 |url=https://archive.org/details/warfarearmedconf0000clod |url-access=registration |date=2008 |publisher=McFarland & Co; |isbn=978-0786433193 |page=[https://archive.org/details/warfarearmedconf0000clod/page/46 46]}}</ref> Significantly outnumbered, he fought Bournonville to a standstill at [[Battle_of_Entzheim|Entzheim]] in early October, followed by a surprise winter attack that culminated in another decisive victory at the [[Battle of Turckheim]] in January 1675.<ref>Lynn, 1999, 127.</ref> \n\nMontecuccoli brought up another 25,000 men and combined with the remnants of Bournonville's force, this meant Turenne was outnumbered once more. By late May, the Imperial army was at [[Oberkirch_(Baden)|Oberkirch]], preparing to take the bridge at [[Kehl]] and re-establish contact with Strasburg. The next two months were spent in a series of marches and counter-marches, with Turenne seeking to remain in close contact with the Imperialists. Local geography restricted them to a relatively narrow corridor between the left bank of the [[Rhine]] and the [[Black Forest]], other factors being a dependence on waterways for moving supplies, the need to obtain forage for cavalry and transport, while persistent rain in the first half of June made movement almost impossible.<ref name=\"De P\u00e9rini, p. 151-152\">De P\u00e9rini, p. 151-152.</ref>  \n\nA number of skirmishes and encounters took place in July as each commander attempted to outwit the other, the Marquis de Vaubrun being wounded in one of these on 24 July. On 25 July, Montecuccoli stopped between [[Gro\u00dfweier]] and [[Sasbach_(Ortenau)|Sasbach]], as he waited for his subordinate [[Aeneas de Caprara]] to rejoin him from [[Offenburg]]. On the morning of 27th, Turenne arrived at [[Battle_of_Salzbach|Salzbach]], looking for an opportunity to attack; he was checking the position of his artillery in the afternoon, when he was killed by a cannonball.<ref>Lynn, 1999, 141.</ref> \n\n==The Battle==\n[[Image:Blondel - Guy Aldonce de Durfort de Lorges (1630-1702) - MV 1042.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Guy Aldonce de Durfort de Lorges]]; Turenne's nephew, who disputed command with Vaubrun]]\nThe news of Turenne's death was initially concealed from the troops, but it soon became common knowledge. Turenne had no direct subordinate but two 'Lieutenant-Generals,' his nephew, the Comte [[Guy_Aldonce_de_Durfort_de_Lorges|de Lorges]] and the Marquis de Vaubrun, who rotated the position on a daily basis. According to another officer, the [[Antoine_de_Pas_de_Feuqui\u00e8res|Marquis de Feuqui\u00e8res]], de Lorges and de Vaubrun now spent the next three days arguing who should assume command, at one point drawing swords on each other in the middle of the camp.<ref>{{cite book |last1=De P\u00e9rini |first1=Hard\u00ff |title=Batailles fran\u00e7aises |date=1896 |publisher=Ernest Flammarion, Paris|page=161 |url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k750505/f162.item.r=Altenheim |accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe French baggage train was stationed in the nearby village of [[Willst\u00e4tt]]; hoping to capture it and re-establish direct communication with Strasburg, a force of Imperial dragoons and cavalry unsuccessfully attacked on 29 July. De Lorge and de Vaubrun finally compromised by agreeing to rotate command daily and on 31 July, the French army moved towards the bridge over the Rhine at [[Altenheim]], a small town now part of the municipality of [[Neuried]] in [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]]. As they did so, Montecuccoli followed up, once more threatening to take Willst\u00e4tt and the French supplies.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Almon |first1=John |title=A new military dictionary: or, the field of war. Containing a particular account of the most remarkable battles, sieges, bombardments, and relate to Great Britain and her dependencies |date=1760 |publisher=Gale ECCO |isbn=978-1385700778 |page=4 |edition=2018 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=8ulhAAAAcAAJ&pg=PT39&lpg=PT39&dq=battle+of+altenheim#v=onepage&q=battle%20of%20altenheim&f=false}}</ref>   \n\nA second dispute broke out between De Lorges and de Vaubrun as to whether to continue towards the bridge or save the stores. They decided to first destroy the stores, then cross, but the delay left the army divided when night came on 31st, with Vaubrun's vanguard on the French side of the Rhine and the rest under de Lorges yet to cross.<ref name=\"Almon 1760, p. 4\">Almon 1760, p. 4.</ref> \nTo reach the Rhine, de Lorges' troops had to first cross a smaller tributary called the [[Schutter_(Kinzig)|Schutter]]. As they began doing so on 1 August, Montecuccoli attacked, while simultaneously cutting off their retreat by taking the bridge at Altenheim. Vaubrun had been wounded in the leg on 24 July and was tied onto his horse; he counter-attacked with 16 squadrons of cavalry and eight battalions of infantry and was killed in the action, but the Imperialists were driven out of Altenheim. The French rearguard was composed of the ''Brigade de Champagne,'' which included the British regiments; it repulsed a series of assaults and fighting ended around evening, with both sides withdrawing.<ref name=\"Almon 1760, p. 4\">Almon 1760, p. 4.</ref> \n[[File:Louis, Grand Cond\u00e9.PNG|thumb|right|150px|[[Louis,_Grand_Cond\u00e9|le Grand Cond\u00e9]], who replaced Turenne a few days after Altenheim]]\nDe Feuqui\u00e8res, part of the ''Brigade de Champagne,'' described this action in his 'Memoirs' as one of the 'most glorious in the history of France.' The brigade lost 10 captains and 25 lieutenants killed, French casualties being around 3,000 to the Imperialists 4,500.<ref name=\"De P\u00e9rini, p. 161\">De P\u00e9rini, p. 161.</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe French withdrew to [[S\u00e9lestat]] and the [[Louis,_Grand_Cond\u00e9|Prince of Cond\u00e9]] assumed command; he was a capable general, responsible for victory at [[Battle_of_Seneffe|Seneffe]] in 1674 but in poor health and this would be his last campaign. On 11 August, a French force of 15,000 sent to relieve [[Trier]] was defeated at [[Battle_of_Konzer_Br\u00fccke|Konzer Br\u00fccke]] and Trier surrendered in September. Unwilling to risk losing the only remaining French army in the Rhineland and estimating Imperial strength at over 30,000, Cond\u00e9 took up position at the fortified town of [[Ch\u00e2tenois, Bas-Rhin|Ch\u00e2tenois]]. Montecuccoli attempted to lure him out, but with French cavalry raiding his supply lines and winter coming on, he abandoned the attempt, In the first week of November, his army recrossed the Rhine and went into winter quarters.<ref name=\"De P\u00e9rini, p. 168-171\">De P\u00e9rini, p. 168-171.</ref>        \n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* Almon, John; ''A new military dictionary: or, the field of war. Containing a particular account of the most remarkable battles, sieges, bombardments, and relate to Great Britain and her dependencies;'' (First published 1760, Gale ECCO, 2018 ed);\n* Clodfelter, Micheal; ''Warfare and Armed Conflicts: A Statistical Encyclopedia of Casualty and Other Figures, 1494-2007;'' (McFarland & Co, 2008);\n* Davenport, Frances; ''European Treaties bearing on the History of the United States and its Dependencies;'' (Published 1917, Andesite Press, 2017 ed);\n* De P\u00e9rini, Hard\u0